{
  "id": "mmspanish__lesson_B1_081_preterite_vs_imperfect",
  "title": "B1.81 The Preterite vs. Imperfect — Two Ways to Tell the Past",
  "mode": "mix_method",
  "steps": [
    {
      "phase": "english_anchor",
      "line": "In English, we tell the past through simple choices: I went, I was going, I used to go. Spanish splits the past into two lenses—the preterite (pretérito) and the imperfect (imperfecto). English does this by shifting auxiliary verbs or adding context; Spanish does it by changing the verb form itself. The preterite frames finished actions with clear limits: a single event, a completed task, a moment that closes its own story. The imperfect, by contrast, paints motion and background, things still happening, habits, or states of being. Where English leans on time expressions or tone, Spanish embeds the difference right into the verb. It’s not just when something happened, but how the speaker sees time—either as a boundary or as continuity."
    },
    {
      "phase": "system_logic",
      "line": "Both the preterite and imperfect describe the past but from different angles. The **preterite** expresses complete, bounded actions: 'Ayer comí pizza' (Yesterday I ate pizza). It’s the camera flash—the beginning and end are both visible. The **imperfect** expresses ongoing, habitual, or background actions: 'Comía pizza todos los viernes' (I used to eat pizza every Friday). It’s the movie reel—continuous, descriptive, and unhurried.\n\n**Formation:**\n- **Preterite endings**: for -ar verbs: -é, -aste, -ó, -amos, -asteis, -aron; for -er/-ir verbs: -í, -iste, -ió, -imos, -isteis, -ieron. Watch for irregular stems like *tuv-, estuv-, dij-, hic-*, etc.\n- **Imperfect endings**: for -ar verbs: -aba, -abas, -aba, -ábamos, -abais, -aban; for -er/-ir verbs: -ía, -ías, -ía, -íamos, -íais, -ían. Only three irregular verbs: *ser → era*, *ir → iba*, *ver → veía*.\n\n**Usage distinction:**\n- Preterite: single, completed, or interrupting actions.\n- Imperfect: repeated, descriptive, simultaneous, or interrupted actions.\n\nExample of contrast: *Cuando llegué, ella cantaba.* → 'When I arrived (preterite: arrival complete), she was singing (imperfect: ongoing action).' The two tenses can coexist to show interaction between what’s finished and what’s flowing."
    },
    {
      "phase": "meaning_depth",
      "origin": "Spanish inherited both forms from Latin’s past system—perfectum (completed) and imperfectum (not completed).",
      "story": "In Latin, the perfect marked an act seen as whole, a circle closed. The imperfect marked something viewed from within—a scene still alive. Spanish preserved that ancient sense of perspective. The preterite tells history; the imperfect tells memory. The difference isn’t only grammatical but emotional. One closes the door; the other leaves it ajar.\n\nWhen Spanish speakers choose between them, they’re not simply choosing tense—they’re deciding how to frame time. The preterite honors action, the moment something crystallized into result. The imperfect honors duration, the gentle hum of things not yet over. Storytellers know this instinctively. They use preterite to advance the plot, imperfect to breathe in it.\n\nThink of a childhood memory: 'Vivía en una casa pequeña y jugaba con mi perro.' It’s all imperfect because it’s atmosphere—unbroken. But the moment of change—'Un día nos mudamos'—shifts into preterite. That movement between the two is how Spanish animates time: not linear, but rhythmic, like inhaling and exhaling.",
      "wrap_line": "The preterite moves the story; the imperfect makes you feel it."
    },
