      "story": "In Latin, verbs carried philosophy. The perfect was for completed circles; the imperfect was for spirals, motion still in progress. Spanish kept that breath inside its past tense. To speak in the imperfect is to remember while still inside the moment.\n\nWriters love it because it evokes texture—the smell of coffee in a kitchen, the way the street sounded at dusk. It’s how Spanish captures nostalgia and detail. When you say 'Vivía en un pueblo pequeño,' you’re not giving information; you’re giving atmosphere. You bring listeners into that world.\n\nEven emotionally, it mirrors how we recall our own stories—soft edges, recurring gestures, something ongoing in our minds. The imperfect isn’t the past that’s gone; it’s the past that still glows faintly behind the present.",
