  "title": "B1.84 Habit vs. Event — The Border Between Repetition and Moment",
  "mode": "mix_method",
  "steps": [
    {
      "phase": "english_anchor",
      "line": "In English, we rely on context or adverbs to distinguish habits from single actions: I used to run vs. I ran once. Spanish makes that distinction grammatically—through the choice between the imperfect and the preterite. English does this by explaining frequency; Spanish does it by changing the verb’s time lens. The imperfect expresses habits and open-ended repetition; the preterite marks singular or completed events. Where English uses phrasing like 'used to,' 'often,' or 'once,' Spanish simply switches tenses to change how time behaves."
    },
    {
      "phase": "system_logic",
      "line": "To decide between **habit** and **event**, ask: *Was this ongoing or was it bounded?*\n\n**Habit / Imperfect:**\nUse the imperfect for repeated or customary past actions, undefined by count or limit.\n→ 'Corría cada mañana' (I used to run every morning).\n→ 'Siempre comíamos juntos' (We always ate together).\n→ 'De niño veía mucha televisión' (As a child I watched a lot of TV).\n\n**Event / Preterite:**\nUse the preterite for single, completed acts that move the story forward.\n→ 'Corrí una maratón' (I ran a marathon).\n→ 'Comimos juntos ayer' (We ate together yesterday).\n\n**Mixed scenes:**\nOne tense can live inside the other. 'Corría cuando empezó a llover' (I was running when it started to rain). Here, the habitual or continuous action (imperfect) forms the background; the interrupting or singular event (preterite) punctuates it. Spanish rhythm alternates between these two layers to build narrative texture.\n\n**Practical rule:** Habit equals open time; event equals closed time. Use imperfect when the story breathes, preterite when it beats."
    },
    {
      "phase": "meaning_depth",
      "origin": "This distinction arose from Latin’s split between 'imperfectum' (ongoing) and 'perfectum' (completed), inherited almost unchanged by Spanish.",
      "story": "In Latin storytelling, tense choice was perspective—either inside the motion or outside observing it. Spanish inherited that dual view. To speak in the imperfect is to wander within memory, feeling repetition as part of life’s rhythm. To speak in the preterite is to stand outside, noting that something began and ended.\n\nHuman experience needs both. We live habits—the routines that build identity—and we live events—the moments that define change. Spanish doesn’t moralize between them; it simply records time truthfully. 'Trabajaba mucho' describes existence. 'Trabajé diez horas' measures it. The first feels like a life; the second feels like a day.\n\nWriters use this contrast deliberately. The imperfect paints continuity, context, and humanity. The preterite drives tension and plot. Between them, Spanish finds its heartbeat: one pulse slow and steady, the other sharp and brief. Together they make time believable.",
      "wrap_line": "Imperfect is the melody of routine; preterite is the drumbeat of change—time’s two rhythms sharing the same song."
