{
  "id": "mmspanish__lesson_B1_088_contrast_and_opposition_clauses",
  "title": "B1.88 Contrast and Opposition Clauses — The Grammar of Balance",
  "mode": "mix_method",
  "steps": [
    {
      "phase": "english_anchor",
      "line": "In English, we use but, although, even though, and however to show contrast. Spanish does this too—but with an extra layer of precision and musicality. English separates contrast by sentence breaks; Spanish folds it into the rhythm of the clause. English does this by placing conjunctions at predictable spots; Spanish changes connector strength to adjust tone, emphasis, and tension. These words don’t just link opposites—they balance thought."
    },
    {
      "phase": "system_logic",
      "line": "Spanish uses **contrast and concession clauses** to express opposition, limitation, or contrast in logic or tone. Each connector signals a slightly different level of resistance.\n\n**Simple contrast:**\n- **pero** → but (neutral, most common): 'Quise ir, pero no pude.' (I wanted to go, but I couldn’t.)\n- **sino / sino que** → but rather (correcting a negative idea): 'No vino Pedro, sino Juan.' (It wasn’t Pedro who came, but Juan.) Use *sino que* before a full clause.\n\n**Concession / contrast with nuance:**\n- **aunque** → although / even though: 'Aunque llovía, salimos.' (Although it was raining, we went out.)\n  - With **indicative**, it expresses a known fact (Although it was raining...).\n  - With **subjunctive**, it shows uncertainty or concession (Even if it rains...).\n- **a pesar de (que)** → in spite of (the fact that): 'A pesar de que estaba cansado, trabajó.' (In spite of being tired, he worked.)\n- **sin embargo / no obstante** → however / nevertheless: transition phrases that contrast full sentences rather than clauses. 'Estaba cansado; sin embargo, trabajó.'\n\n**Position and tone:**\nPlace *pero* mid-sentence for conversational rhythm, *sin embargo* at the start for literary contrast. Spanish prefers variety—repetition of *pero* sounds heavy. Alternate *aunque*, *aun así*, or *sin embargo* to modulate texture.\n\n**Subtle contrasts:** *aunque* softens disagreement; *pero* states it plainly; *sin embargo* dignifies it; *sino* corrects it. Tone lives in choice."
    },
    {
      "phase": "meaning_depth",
      "origin": "Contrast clauses descend from Latin particles 'sed', 'autem', and 'quamvis', used to weigh rhetorical balance in debate and prose.",
      "story": "For classical speakers, argument was art. Latin trained its speakers to balance thought like scales—each idea needing its counterweight. Spanish kept that equilibrium. Its contrast markers are not blunt tools but instruments of tone. *Pero* feels human—simple opposition. *Sin embargo* carries patience, signaling reflection. *Aunque* allows contradiction without breaking the flow, a word built for coexistence.\n\nIn speech, these markers reveal personality. Quick speakers favor *pero*—it moves fast, emotional and clear. Thoughtful narrators prefer *sin embargo*, letting silence cushion their contrast. *A pesar de que* signals persistence, struggle beneath politeness. Each phrase pulls meaning like tension on a string.\n\nWriters use contrast to give stories rhythm. 'Era pobre, pero feliz.' Two ideas hold hands instead of fighting. Spanish opposition isn’t confrontation—it’s harmony through difference. When you hear these connectors in poetry or politics, they act as pivots, allowing complexity without chaos. The language doesn’t erase contradiction; it frames it, teaching that balance is not weakness but elegance.",
      "wrap_line": "Spanish contrast words don’t divide—they reconcile—grammar built to keep opposites in conversation."
    },
    {
      "phase": "context_scene",
      "npc": "teacher",
      "es": "[locked]",
      "you": "[locked]"
    },
    {
      "phase": "examples",
      "items": [
        { "en": "I wanted to go, but I couldn’t → quise ir, pero no pude.", "es": "[locked]" },
        { "en": "Although it was raining, we went out → aunque llovía, salimos.", "es": "[locked]" },
        { "en": "He was tired; nevertheless, he worked → estaba cansado; sin embargo, trabajó.", "es": "[locked]" }
