  "id": "mmspanish__lesson_B1_091_conditional_clauses",
  "title": "B1.91 Conditional Clauses — The Grammar of Possibility",
  "mode": "mix_method",
  "steps": [
    {
      "phase": "english_anchor",
      "line": "In English, we build conditions with if and would: If it rains, I’ll stay home; If I had time, I would go. Spanish does the same with si-clauses, but its system is more elegant and precise. English marks possibility through auxiliary verbs; Spanish expresses it through the marriage of tense and mood. English shows probability through tone; Spanish encodes it in structure. Where English separates thought into two halves, Spanish fuses them—cause and imagined effect bound in grammatical symmetry."
    },
    {
      "phase": "system_logic",
      "line": "**Core structure:** Conditional clauses use *si* (if) plus the appropriate tense pattern. The logic is simple: the more real the condition, the closer its verb is to the present.\n\n**1️⃣ Real or likely situations (present → future):**\n*Si + present indicative → future / imperative.*\n'**Si llueve, me quedaré en casa.**' (If it rains, I’ll stay home.)\nThe speaker sees this as possible.\n\n**2️⃣ Hypothetical situations (past contrary to present):**\n*Si + imperfect subjunctive → conditional.*\n'**Si tuviera dinero, viajaría.**' (If I had money, I would travel.)\nThis pattern imagines an unreal present or ongoing condition.\n\n**3️⃣ Impossible past situations (past contrary to past):**\n*Si + pluperfect subjunctive → conditional perfect.*\n'**Si hubieras venido, te habrías divertido.**' (If you had come, you would have had fun.)\nThis combination revisits lost chances, unchangeable history.\n\n**Important notes:**\n- Never use *si + future*. The future meaning lives in the main clause, not in *si.*\n- Conditional verbs (*viajaría, iría, sería*) share endings: *-ía, -ías, -ía, -íamos, -íais, -ían.*\n- Subjunctive forms for unreality: *tuviera / tuviese, viniera / viniese, fuera / fuese.* Both are correct; style decides.\n\nConditionals can invert order without changing meaning: 'Me quedaré en casa si llueve.' They can also soften requests politely: 'Si pudiera, le ayudaría.' (If I could, I would help you.) Spanish treats condition as not just grammar—it’s diplomacy."
    },
    {
      "phase": "meaning_depth",
      "origin": "The conditional structure in Spanish evolved from Latin’s use of the subjunctive in protasis and apodosis—two halves of rhetorical possibility.",
