  "id": "mmspanish__lesson_B1_092_present_perfect",
  "title": "B1.92 The Present Perfect — The Grammar of Recent Memory",
  "mode": "mix_method",
  "steps": [
    {
      "phase": "english_anchor",
      "line": "In English, we say things like I’ve eaten, She has gone, They’ve just arrived to describe experiences that link the past to the present. Spanish does the same with the **pretérito perfecto compuesto**, or present perfect, but the emotional center shifts slightly. English does this by treating the past as still connected; Spanish uses it to acknowledge a past that still matters now. English focuses on continuity; Spanish focuses on relevance. The result is the same surface meaning—recent or unfinished time—but in Spanish, the grammar carries awareness: what has happened still echoes."
    },
    {
      "phase": "system_logic",
      "line": "The **present perfect** combines **haber** (to have) in the present tense with the **past participle** of the main verb. \n\n**Formation:** haber + participle\n- he, has, ha, hemos, habéis, han + -ado / -ido forms.\n→ 'He comido' (I have eaten), 'Has estudiado' (You have studied), 'Hemos vivido' (We have lived).\n\n**Irregular participles:** *escrito, visto, roto, puesto, dicho, hecho, abierto, muerto, vuelto, descubierto.*\n\n**Usage:**\n1️⃣ **Recent past with present relevance:** 'He perdido las llaves' (I’ve lost my keys—still relevant now).\n2️⃣ **Life experiences:** 'He visitado México dos veces.' (I’ve been to Mexico twice.)\n3️⃣ **Unfinished time periods:** 'Este año ha llovido mucho.' (It has rained a lot this year—year still ongoing.)\n4️⃣ **News and announcements:** 'Ha habido un accidente.' (There’s been an accident.)\n\n**Regional difference:** In Spain, the present perfect often replaces the simple preterite for recent or still-relevant events—'Hoy he comido temprano.' In much of Latin America, speakers use the simple preterite instead—'Hoy comí temprano.' Both are correct; usage depends on regional rhythm and perception of immediacy."
    },
    {
      "phase": "meaning_depth",
      "origin": "The form comes from Latin’s perfectum periphrasticum, originally a structure meaning 'to have something done'—a sense of possession over the past.",
      "story": "Latin speakers once said 'habeo scriptum'—I have it written—to mean both physical possession and completed action. Over centuries, that expression turned inward: 'I have written' became not about the object, but about the experience. Spanish preserved that subtlety. When you say 'He vivido,' you’re not counting events—you’re claiming life’s weight.\n\nCulturally, the present perfect reveals Spanish sensitivity to emotional relevance. A thing isn’t just done; it stays. 'He pensado mucho en ti' carries tenderness because it places memory inside the now. Spanish tenses map not just time, but feeling toward time.\n\nWriters use this tense for reflection. It slows narrative tempo, letting action breathe. 'Ha pasado el verano, y el mar aún huele a sal.' The act is complete, yet the presence remains. It’s grammar designed for introspection, built for speakers who sense the past walking beside them.",
      "wrap_line": "The present perfect is Spanish mindfulness—grammar that holds memory gently in the present moment."
