  "id": "mmspanish__lesson_B1_093_past_perfect",
  "title": "B1.93 The Past Perfect — The Grammar of Before the Before",
  "mode": "mix_method",
  "steps": [
    {
      "phase": "english_anchor",
      "line": "In English, we use had + past participle to reach deeper into the past: I had gone, She had finished. Spanish mirrors this with **pretérito pluscuamperfecto**—haber in the imperfect + the past participle. English does this by context, marking one event as prior to another; Spanish does it structurally, embedding chronology into the verb. English tells time; Spanish layers it, showing memory nested inside memory."
    },
    {
      "phase": "system_logic",
      "line": "The **past perfect (pluscuamperfecto)** expresses an action completed **before** another past action. It’s used to establish sequence or background within the past narrative.\n\n**Formation:**\n**haber (imperfect) + past participle**\n- había, habías, había, habíamos, habíais, habían + -ado / -ido.\n→ 'Había comido' (I had eaten), 'Habíamos terminado' (We had finished).\n\n**Irregular participles**: *abierto, dicho, hecho, puesto, visto, vuelto, escrito, roto, muerto, descubierto.*\n\n**Usage:**\n1️⃣ To indicate one past action preceding another: 'Cuando llegué, ella ya había salido.' (When I arrived, she had already left.)\n2️⃣ To add background or cause: 'No tenía hambre porque había almorzado.' (I wasn’t hungry because I had eaten lunch.)\n3️⃣ In reported speech: 'Dijo que había estudiado antes del examen.' (He said he had studied before the test.)\n\nThe key is reference order. The main past event uses preterite or imperfect; the earlier one takes the past perfect. It’s the historian’s tense—always pointing backward from the past to a deeper layer."
