    },
    {
      "phase": "system_logic",
      "line": "**Formation:** The future tense in Spanish is one of the simplest: attach endings directly to the infinitive. \n\n**Endings (for all verbs):** -é, -ás, -á, -emos, -éis, -án.\nExamples: *hablaré* (I will speak), *comerás* (you will eat), *vivirán* (they will live). The same endings apply to -ar, -er, and -ir verbs.\n\n**Irregular stems:** *tendr-* (tener), *saldr-* (salir), *vendr-* (venir), *har-* (hacer), *dir-* (decir), *podr-* (poder), *habr-* (haber), *sabr-* (saber), *querr-* (querer), *pondr-* (poner), *valdr-* (valer). Add the same endings to these stems.\n\n**Uses:**\n1️⃣ **Simple future / Intention:** 'Mañana estudiaré' (Tomorrow I’ll study.)\n2️⃣ **Promise or determination:** 'Te ayudaré.' (I will help you.)\n3️⃣ **Assumption or probability in the present:** 'Estará en casa.' (He must be home / He’s probably home.)\n4️⃣ **Formal prediction or plan:** 'Habrá lluvia mañana.' (There will be rain tomorrow.)\n\n**Notes:**\n- In conversation, many speakers use *ir + a + infinitive* to express planned future: 'Voy a estudiar mañana.' The pure future (*estudiaré*) feels firmer, sometimes more formal or emotional. Spanish thus offers two ways to speak of what’s next—one pragmatic, one poetic."
