{
  "id": "mmspanish__lesson_B1_095_conditional_tense",
  "title": "B1.95 The Conditional Tense — The Grammar of Courtesy and Hypothesis",
  "mode": "mix_method",
  "steps": [
    {
      "phase": "english_anchor",
      "line": "In English, we use would to imagine, soften, or show politeness: I would go, I’d like that, Would you help me? Spanish does this with the **conditional tense**, but with greater elegance and range. English does this by tone and context; Spanish builds it directly into verb endings. English uses would to signal distance from reality or time; Spanish turns that distance into formality, gentleness, or reflection. Where English stretches mood through phrasing, Spanish refines it through structure—logic and kindness sharing one tense."
    },
    {
      "phase": "system_logic",
      "line": "**Formation:** Add conditional endings to the infinitive of any verb—no stem changes.\n\n**Endings (for -ar, -er, -ir verbs):** -ía, -ías, -ía, -íamos, -íais, -ían.\nExamples: *hablaría* (I would speak), *comerías* (you would eat), *vivirían* (they would live).\n\n**Irregular stems (same as future):** *tendr-* (tener), *saldr-* (salir), *vendr-* (venir), *har-* (hacer), *dir-* (decir), *podr-* (poder), *habr-* (haber), *sabr-* (saber), *querr-* (querer), *pondr-* (poner), *valdr-* (valer).\n\n**Uses:**\n1️⃣ **Polite requests or offers:** '¿Podrías ayudarme?' (Could you help me?) 'Querría un café, por favor.' (I’d like a coffee, please.)\n2️⃣ **Hypothetical situations:** 'Si tuviera tiempo, viajaría más.' (If I had time, I’d travel more.)\n3️⃣ **Future in the past:** 'Dijo que llegaría a las ocho.' (He said he’d arrive at eight.)\n4️⃣ **Probable past (speculation):** 'Serían las diez cuando llamó.' (It must have been ten when he called.)\n\nThe conditional smooths conversation. It signals respect, humility, and possibility. Spanish uses it as social lubricant—where English adds words like maybe or please, Spanish reshapes time itself to soften tone."
    },
    {
      "phase": "meaning_depth",
      "origin": "The conditional developed from Latin’s periphrastic 'infinitive + habere' construction, meaning 'to have to,' which gradually evolved into 'would.'",
