    },
    {
      "phase": "system_logic",
      "line": "**Core function:** The subjunctive in Spanish goes beyond emotion—it organizes uncertainty into categories of hope, purpose, and possibility. The triggers depend on meaning, not tense.\n\n**1️⃣ Expressions of desire and hope:**\n- *Ojalá (que)* → 'I hope / may it be so': 'Ojalá que vengas pronto.' (I hope you come soon.)\n- *Esperar que* → to hope that, *desear que* → to wish that, *preferir que* → to prefer that.\nThese use the **present subjunctive** for future possibilities.\n\n**2️⃣ Purpose and condition:**\n- *Para que* → so that: 'Te lo digo para que lo sepas.' (I’m telling you so that you know.)\n- *A menos que* → unless, *con tal de que* → provided that, *antes de que* → before.\nThese introduce conditions that may or may not occur, always requiring the subjunctive.\n\n**3️⃣ Uncertainty and reaction:**\n- *Dudar que*, *no estar seguro de que*, *no creer que* → trigger the subjunctive: 'Dudo que venga.' (I doubt he’s coming.)\nWhen the speaker regains confidence, the indicative returns: 'Sé que viene.' (I know he’s coming.)\n\n**4️⃣ After certain temporal phrases referring to future or uncertain time:** *cuando, en cuanto, tan pronto como, hasta que.*\n→ 'Cuando llegue, te avisaré.' (When he arrives, I’ll let you know.) Present form, but subjunctive mood—future uncertainty drives it.\n\nThe subjunctive creates grammar for possibilities before they exist. English uses separate phrases to achieve nuance; Spanish uses internal logic, turning verbs into mirrors of belief."
