      "line": "In English, we show influence and reaction through tone or separate verbs: I want him to go, I suggest that she leave, It’s good that you came. Spanish expresses all of this through the **subjunctive mood**, turning intention, reaction, and persuasion into structure. English does this by building an extra clause with to or that; Spanish does it directly by conjugating the following verb in the subjunctive. The difference is clarity—English hints at influence; Spanish encodes it. Emotion and command become grammar."
    },
    {
      "phase": "system_logic",
      "line": "**Influence verbs** trigger the subjunctive when one person’s will affects another’s action. These verbs express requests, advice, demands, permission, or influence.\n\n**Common verbs of influence:** *querer, pedir, recomendar, sugerir, aconsejar, prohibir, permitir, insistir en, exigir, decir* (when meaning 'to tell someone to').\n\n→ 'Quiero que vengas.' (I want you to come.)\n→ 'Te recomiendo que estudies más.' (I recommend that you study more.)\n→ 'Nos prohibieron que habláramos.' (They forbade us to speak.)\n\n**Structure:**\nMain clause (verb of influence) + que + subordinate clause (verb in subjunctive).\n- The subjects must differ: 'Quiero que vengas' (I ≠ you). If they are the same, use the infinitive: 'Quiero venir temprano.'\n\n**Reaction and emotion:**\nWhen verbs express feelings about another action, the subjunctive marks that reaction.\n→ 'Me alegra que estés aquí.' (I’m glad you’re here.)\n→ 'Temo que no lleguen a tiempo.' (I fear they won’t arrive on time.)\n→ 'Siento que hayas perdido tu vuelo.' (I’m sorry you missed your flight.)\n\n**Subtle rules:**\n- *Decir que* can take indicative when relaying facts ('Dice que viene') and subjunctive when giving commands ('Dice que vengas').\n- *Esperar que*, *rogar que*, *sugerir que* always pull the subjunctive—they belong to the grammar of persuasion.\n- Emotion verbs take the subjunctive when there’s uncertainty about the result or difference in subject.\n\nIn short: **Subjunctive = interaction between wills.** The stronger the emotional or persuasive charge, the clearer its need for the mood."
