  "id": "mmspanish__lesson_B1_100_imperative_mood",
  "title": "B1.100 The Imperative Mood — The Grammar of Command and Invitation",
  "mode": "mix_method",
  "steps": [
    {
      "phase": "english_anchor",
      "line": "In English, we issue commands simply by using the base form of a verb: Sit down, Come here, Don’t move. Spanish also commands—but it does so through a **system** that balances authority, familiarity, and respect. English does this by tone; Spanish encodes it into structure. The **imperative mood** can sound warm, sharp, or formal depending on formality and relationship. Where English uses the same shape for all, Spanish tailors the command to context—grammar becomes social awareness."
    },
    {
      "phase": "system_logic",
      "line": "**Definition:** The **imperative mood** expresses orders, instructions, invitations, and advice. Spanish commands change form based on who is being addressed (tú, usted, vosotros, ustedes, nosotros) and whether the statement is positive or negative.\n\n**Affirmative forms:**\n- *tú*: third-person singular of the present indicative (drop the –s): *habla, come, vive.*\n- *usted*: third-person singular of the present subjunctive: *hable, coma, viva.*\n- *vosotros*: replace final –r of infinitive with –d: *hablad, comed, vivid.*\n- *ustedes*: third-person plural of subjunctive: *hablen, coman, vivan.*\n- *nosotros*: first-person plural of subjunctive: *hablemos, comamos, vivamos.*\n\n**Negative forms:** all persons use the present **subjunctive**.\n- *no hables, no coma, no habléis, no hablen, no hablemos.*\n\n**Irregular verbs:** *decir → di / diga*, *hacer → haz / haga*, *ir → ve / vaya*, *poner → pon / ponga*, *salir → sal / salga*, *ser → sé / sea*, *tener → ten / tenga*, *venir → ven / venga.*\n\n**Pronouns:** attach to affirmative commands (*dímelo*), but precede negative ones (*no me lo digas*).\n\n**Function and tone:** The imperative doesn’t only order—it can encourage (*hazlo*), invite (*ven conmigo*), warn (*ten cuidado*), or comfort (*no llores*). Spanish commands breathe nuance: the same structure can bless or scold depending on rhythm and register."
