{
  "id": "mmspanish__lesson_B1_101_passive_voice",
  "title": "B1.101 The Passive Voice — The Grammar of Focus and Perspective",
  "mode": "mix_method",
  "steps": [
    {
      "phase": "english_anchor",
      "line": "In English, we use the passive voice when we care more about the action than the actor: The door was opened, The song was written by her. Spanish also uses the **passive**, but it prefers it with purpose—it rearranges focus, not responsibility. English does this mechanically by flipping subject and object; Spanish does it thoughtfully, deciding whether to highlight the event itself or the people involved. Where English uses the passive often to sound neutral, Spanish uses it to sound elegant, distant, or formal. It’s grammar that shifts the camera angle."
    },
    {
      "phase": "system_logic",
      "line": "**Formation:** Spanish has two main types of passives.\n\n**1️⃣ Ser + past participle (true passive):** Used when the agent is explicit or implied.\n- *El libro fue escrito por García Márquez.* (The book was written by García Márquez.)\n- *Las casas serán construidas el próximo año.* (The houses will be built next year.)\nThe verb *ser* matches the tense of the action, and the past participle agrees in gender and number with the subject (*escrito / escrita / escritos / escritas*).\n\n**2️⃣ Se passive (impersonal or reflexive passive):** Used more often in modern Spanish, especially in spoken form.\n- *Se vende casa.* (House for sale / A house is sold.)\n- *Se publicaron los resultados.* (The results were published.)\nHere *se* replaces the explicit agent, focusing on the action itself. The verb agrees with the object that becomes the grammatical subject (*se publicaron resultados*).\n\n**Choosing between forms:**\n- Use *ser + participle* when the performer of the action matters or needs to be stated.\n- Use *se + verb* when the focus is on process or outcome.\n\n**Register:** The *ser* passive is formal and literary; the *se* passive is natural and frequent in everyday Spanish. Both express the same idea: actions exist beyond the individual doing them."
    },
    {
      "phase": "meaning_depth",
      "origin": "The Spanish passive stems from Latin’s perfect participle constructions, used to show reverence toward deeds and to obscure agency.",
      "story": "Latin valued action over ego. In imperial inscriptions, victories were recorded as 'urbs capta est'—'the city was taken'—because history mattered more than generals. Spanish inherited that humility but humanized it. The passive voice lets speakers step aside, giving space to the act or its consequence.\n\nIn literature, it becomes perspective. 'Fue escrito' centers the text, not the author; 'se dice' turns rumor into atmosphere. The *se* passive, in particular, mirrors the communal way Spanish cultures often view responsibility: things happen through many hands. *Se construyó la ciudad* doesn’t hide who built it—it honors collective effort.\n\nStylistically, passives create distance, ceremony, or mystery. Political speeches use them to soften accountability ('Se tomaron decisiones difíciles'); poets use them to elevate tone ('Fueron dichas palabras eternas'). Learning when to use them teaches rhythm, restraint, and subtlety. Spanish doesn’t erase the doer; it just chooses when the deed deserves center stage.",
      "wrap_line": "The passive is Spanish perspective—grammar that honors the act more than the actor."
