{
  "id": "mmspanish__lesson_B1_102_se_constructions",
  "title": "B1.102 The “Se” Constructions — The Grammar of Neutral Action",
  "mode": "mix_method",
  "steps": [
    {
      "phase": "english_anchor",
      "line": "In English, we use vague phrases like people say, one does, or it’s said to avoid naming who acts: People say it’s true, It’s believed, One eats well here. Spanish accomplishes the same with the tiny but powerful **se**. English does this by adding impersonal words; Spanish does it by transforming the sentence itself. Se turns verbs into self-contained actions—events that happen, rather than acts that someone performs. It’s grammar that dissolves ego, shifting focus from who to what."
    },
    {
      "phase": "system_logic",
      "line": "**Definition:** The pronoun **se** can make sentences impersonal, passive, or reflexive depending on structure. It removes the explicit agent while keeping meaning intact.\n\n**1️⃣ Reflexive:** The subject and object are the same.\n- *Se lava las manos.* (He washes his hands.)\n- *Me, te, se, nos, os, se* mark self-directed action.\n\n**2️⃣ Impersonal se:** Describes actions generally, without a subject.\n- *Se vive bien aquí.* (People live well here.)\n- *Se dice que vendrá pronto.* (It’s said he’ll come soon.)\nVerb stays **third-person singular** because there’s no specific subject.\n\n**3️⃣ Passive se:** Similar to passive voice, focuses on the object of action.\n- *Se venden casas.* (Houses are sold.)\n- *Se publicaron los resultados.* (The results were published.)\nVerb agrees in number with the object.\n\n**4️⃣ Involuntary or accidental se:** Used to soften or remove blame.\n- *Se me cayó el vaso.* (I dropped the glass / The glass fell on me.)\n- *Se nos olvidó la cita.* (We forgot / The appointment slipped our minds.)\nThis shows humility or shared error—the action happens to the speaker rather than being performed by them.\n\n**Summary:**\n| Type | Function | Example |\n|------|-----------|----------|\n| Reflexive | self-action | *Se viste.* |\n| Impersonal | general truth | *Se vive bien.* |\n| Passive | object focus | *Se venden flores.* |\n| Accidental | unintentional act | *Se me rompió el vaso.* |\n\nSe is elastic—it changes shape depending on purpose but always softens tone, spreading action into context rather than pointing at a doer."
    },
    {
      "phase": "meaning_depth",
      "origin": "The pronoun *se* evolved from Latin’s reflexive pronoun *sē*, originally meaning 'himself / herself,' which later broadened to mark impersonal and middle voices.",
      "story": "In Latin, reflexive verbs mirrored the self. Over centuries, Spanish transformed that mirror into mist—*se* began reflecting not just the subject, but society’s relationship with responsibility. *Se dice* allows distance; *se me cayó* turns blame into empathy. Instead of 'I failed,' Spanish says 'it happened to me.' The shift is cultural: language itself offers compassion.\n\nThis tiny word reveals the Spanish instinct for collective perspective. Rather than isolating the actor, *se* integrates experience into community or circumstance. 'Se vive bien en México' doesn’t mean everyone lives well; it means life, as a concept, flows well there.\n\nWriters love *se* for its ambiguity. It allows suggestion instead of assertion, mystery instead of certainty. Political speech uses it to soften: 'Se cometieron errores' (Mistakes were made). Poets use it to elevate: 'Se ama sin saber por qué.' Grammar turns existential—it becomes a lens through which experience happens without borders.",
      "wrap_line": "The word *se* is Spanish humility—grammar that lets life happen without assigning blame or pride."
    },
    {
      "phase": "context_scene",
      "npc": "teacher",
