{
  "id": "mmspanish__lesson_B1_104_por_vs_para",
  "title": "B1.104 Por vs. Para — The Grammar of Purpose and Path",
  "mode": "mix_method",
  "steps": [
    {
      "phase": "english_anchor",
      "line": "In English, we often use for to mean both purpose and path: This gift is for you, I walked for an hour, We left for Madrid. Spanish divides that one word into two: **por** and **para**. English does this by stretching meaning; Spanish does it by specializing meaning. Para looks forward—it expresses destination, goal, or purpose. Por looks around—it expresses cause, duration, or movement through. English leaves you guessing; Spanish lets you choose how you travel through time, space, and intention."
    },
    {
      "phase": "system_logic",
      "line": "**1️⃣ PARA → Destination, purpose, recipient, comparison, and deadlines.**\n→ Think of para as forward motion—toward a goal or endpoint.\n- **Purpose / goal:** 'Estudio para aprender.' (I study in order to learn.)\n- **Destination:** 'Salgo para Madrid.' (I’m leaving for Madrid.)\n- **Recipient:** 'Este regalo es para ti.' (This gift is for you.)\n- **Deadline:** 'La tarea es para mañana.' (The homework is for tomorrow.)\n- **Comparison or opinion:** 'Para ser tan joven, sabe mucho.' (For being so young, he knows a lot.)\n\n**2️⃣ POR → Cause, means, exchange, movement through, duration, or gratitude.**\n→ Think of por as motion within—moving through reason, method, or context.\n- **Cause / motive:** 'Lo hice por ti.' (I did it because of you.)\n- **Means / method:** 'Te llamé por teléfono.' (I called you by phone.)\n- **Movement through:** 'Caminamos por el parque.' (We walked through the park.)\n- **Exchange:** 'Pagué veinte euros por el libro.' (I paid twenty euros for the book.)\n- **Duration:** 'Estudié por tres horas.' (I studied for three hours.)\n- **Passive agent:** 'Fue escrito por Cervantes.' (It was written by Cervantes.)\n\n**Quick test:**\n| Meaning | Word | Mental image |\n|----------|------|---------------|\n| Toward purpose | para | arrow pointing ahead |\n| Through cause or method | por | circle of movement |\n\n**Idiomatic uses:**\n- *Por eso* (that’s why), *por favor* (please), *por lo general* (generally), *para siempre* (forever), *para entonces* (by then)."
    },
    {
      "phase": "meaning_depth",
      "origin": "Por and para both descend from Latin prepositions 'per' (through) and 'pro' (for, on behalf of), which once described motion and advocacy.",
      "story": "In Latin, 'per' traced the traveler’s path, while 'pro' marked purpose or defense. Spanish kept that geography of meaning. *Por* belongs to the journey, *para* belongs to the goal. They divide the human experience between motion and intention.\n\nIn practice, Spanish speakers feel this distinction rather than analyze it. *Por amor* means out of love—motive. *Para amar* means in order to love—purpose. The prepositions become a philosophy: one explains why, the other explains why not yet.\n\nWriters play with their tension. In Neruda’s letters, 'Lucho por ti, vivo para ti' separates struggle and devotion—the effort versus its destination. Everyday speech reflects the same awareness. *Gracias por venir* thanks someone for their act; *esto es para ti* dedicates the result. It’s how Spanish keeps action and meaning in dialogue, never collapsing them into a single “for.”",
      "wrap_line": "Por and para form the compass of Spanish—grammar guiding both motive and direction."
    },
    {
      "phase": "context_scene",
      "npc": "teacher",
      "es": "[locked]",
      "you": "[locked]"
    },
