  "id": "mmspanish__lesson_B1_108_volver_vs_regresar",
  "title": "B1.108 Volver vs. Regresar — The Grammar of Return and Repetition",
  "mode": "mix_method",
  "steps": [
    {
      "phase": "english_anchor",
      "line": "In English, we usually say come back or return to express going back to a place or situation: I came back home, She returned to work, It happened again. Spanish divides these ideas into two related verbs—**volver** and **regresar**. English does this by reusing one phrase; Spanish distinguishes physical return from cyclical action. **Volver** emphasizes coming back or doing something again, while **regresar** highlights the act of returning to a place or state. English flattens time into motion; Spanish traces the loop itself."
    },
    {
      "phase": "system_logic",
      "line": "**1️⃣ VOLVER → To return, to come back, or to do again.**\nDerived from Latin *volvere* (to roll, to turn), *volver* is cyclical—it carries the sense of turning around, repetition, or reversal.\n- **Physical return:** 'Vuelvo a casa a las seis.' (I return home at six.)\n- **Repetition (with *a* + infinitive):** 'Volver a + verb' = to do again. 'Volvimos a intentarlo.' (We tried again.)\n- **Emotional / abstract return:** 'Volver la vista atrás.' (To look back.)\n\n**2️⃣ REGRESAR → To go back or come back (neutral and directional).**\nFrom Latin *regressus*, meaning to walk back or retreat.\n- *Regresamos ayer de las vacaciones.* (We came back from vacation yesterday.)\n- *¿Cuándo regresas al trabajo?* (When are you returning to work?)\n\n**3️⃣ Contrast:**\n- *Volver* can be reflexive (*volver(se)*), meaning to turn oneself or to become: 'Se volvió loco.' (He went crazy.)\n- *Regresar* is never reflexive in that sense—it simply describes physical or situational return.\n\n**4️⃣ Quick guide:**\n| Function | Verb | Example |\n|-----------|------|----------|\n| Return home (neutral) | regresar | *Regresé tarde.* |\n| Return again / repeat action | volver | *Volví a llamarte.* |\n| Become / emotional shift | volverse | *Se volvió serio.* |\n\nBoth verbs can overlap in casual speech, but *volver* carries rhythm—it bends time backward. *Regresar* stays literal—it retraces steps."
