  "id": "mmspanish__lesson_B1_109_quedar_vs_quedarse",
  "title": "B1.109 Quedar vs. Quedarse — The Grammar of Remaining and Becoming",
  "mode": "mix_method",
  "steps": [
    {
      "phase": "english_anchor",
      "line": "In English, we use stay, remain, or end up to describe what’s left or what results: We stayed home, Only two were left, He ended up tired. Spanish divides these ideas between **quedar** and **quedarse**. English does this by adding prepositions or adverbs; Spanish does it through motion of meaning. **Quedar** focuses on what remains or what is arranged; **quedarse** adds the self—it’s what a person becomes, keeps, or experiences as result. One describes what’s left; the other describes how you live with it."
    },
    {
      "phase": "system_logic",
      "line": "**1️⃣ QUEDAR → To remain, to be left, to agree on, or to suit.**\nNon-reflexive, external, often about things, numbers, or plans.\n- *Quedan dos entradas.* (Two tickets remain.)\n- *¿En qué quedamos?* (What did we agree on?)\n- *Ese color te queda bien.* (That color suits you.)\n- *La tienda queda lejos.* (The store is located far away.)\nHere, *quedar* functions as “to remain,” “to be situated,” or “to suit.” It deals with what exists outside the self—results, availability, or location.\n\n**2️⃣ QUEDARSE → To stay, keep, or end up.**\nReflexive, internal—expressing a state that happens to or within someone.\n- *Me quedé en casa.* (I stayed home.)\n- *Nos quedamos sin dinero.* (We ended up without money.)\n- *Se quedó dormido.* (He fell asleep.)\n- *Te quedas con el coche.* (You’re keeping the car.)\n\n**3️⃣ Difference in focus:**\n| Type | Verb | Perspective |\n|------|------|--------------|\n| External / situational | quedar | Remaining or arranging something |\n| Internal / experiential | quedarse | Experiencing or becoming something |\n\n**4️⃣ Idioms:**\n- *Quedar bien / mal* → to make a good or bad impression.\n- *Quedarse callado* → to stay silent.\n- *Quedarse sin + noun* → to run out of something.\n- *Quedarse + adjective* → to end up in a new state: *Se quedó sorprendido.* (He was left surprised.)\n\n**Summary:** *Quedar* talks about the world’s leftovers; *quedarse* talks about the self’s aftermath."
