      "phase": "meaning_depth",
      "origin": "These verbs stem from Latin actions of motion and creation—*ponere* (to place), *facere* (to make), and *volvere* (to turn)—three metaphors for transformation.",
      "story": "Ancient Latin described change through the body: to place, to make, to turn. Spanish kept this anatomy of becoming. *Ponerse* speaks of surface change—the blush, the shift, the moment emotion paints the skin. *Hacerse* belongs to intention—the change shaped by work or identity. *Volverse* belongs to destiny—the kind of change that happens to you, not by you.\n\nThe distinction reveals Spanish depth of empathy toward transformation. The language doesn’t flatten growth into one verb—it measures the force behind it. To *hacerse fuerte* (become strong) honors will; to *volverse amargo* (become bitter) recognizes pain; to *ponerse feliz* (get happy) celebrates reaction. Each carries emotional physics.\n\nWriters use these verbs to map character arcs: 'Se hizo sabio' for earned wisdom, 'Se volvió solitario' for retreat, 'Se puso pálido' for shock. The audience doesn’t just see change; they feel how it happened. Spanish grammar, like life, distinguishes between effort and accident, moment and permanence.",
      "wrap_line": "Ponerse, hacerse, and volverse turn change into story—grammar that explains not just what shifts, but why and how deeply."
