  "mode": "mix_method",
  "steps": [
    {
      "phase": "english_anchor",
      "line": "In English, we use finish and end to describe the close of something: I finished the book, The meeting ended, We’re done. Spanish shares this idea but divides it into two verbs—**acabar** and **terminar**—because not all endings are the same. English does this with tone; Spanish does it with cause. **Terminar** marks completion—something reaching its natural or scheduled end. **Acabar** marks cessation—something stopping or running out. English flattens finality; Spanish distinguishes between what ends by design and what ends by exhaustion."
    },
    {
      "phase": "system_logic",
      "line": "**1️⃣ TERMINAR → To finish, complete, or conclude something (intentional or structured).**\n- *Terminamos el proyecto.* (We finished the project.)\n- *La película termina a las nueve.* (The movie ends at nine.)\n- *Termina tus deberes.* (Finish your homework.)\nImplies a process that arrives where it was meant to. *Terminar* belongs to closure with order or intent.\n\n**2️⃣ ACABAR → To run out, end, or cease (often unplanned or felt).**\n- *Se acabó el agua.* (The water ran out.)\n- *Acabamos cansados.* (We ended up tired.)\n- *Acabé de llegar.* (I just arrived.)\nThe construction *acabar de + infinitive* means 'to have just done something.'\n\n**3️⃣ Structural difference:**\n| Function | Verb | Focus |\n|-----------|------|--------|\n| Planned completion | terminar | purpose / schedule |\n| Natural or sudden end | acabar | result / exhaustion |\n\n**4️⃣ Reflexive uses:**\nBoth can act reflexively to mark absolute or mutual end.\n- *Se terminó la paciencia.* (Patience ran out completely.)\n- *Se acabó la fiesta.* (The party’s over.)\n\n**5️⃣ Idioms:**\n- *Acabar con algo* → to destroy or wipe out something. 'El fuego acabó con el bosque.' (The fire destroyed the forest.)\n- *Terminar por + infinitive* → to end up doing something. 'Terminó por aceptarlo.' (He ended up accepting it.)\n\nIn conversation, *terminar* feels procedural, *acabar* emotional. Spanish separates the end of action from the end of energy."
