  "id": "mmspanish__lesson_B1_114_llevar_vs_tener",
  "title": "B1.114 Llevar vs. Tener — The Grammar of Possession and Duration",
  "mode": "mix_method",
  "steps": [
    {
      "phase": "english_anchor",
      "line": "In English, we mostly use have for everything: I have a car, I have a cold, I’ve been studying, I have my hair long. Spanish divides this wide net into two verbs—**tener** and **llevar**—because it treats possession and process as different states of being. English does this by context; Spanish does it by meaning. **Tener** expresses possession, state, or obligation—what you hold or experience. **Llevar** expresses ongoing time or carried condition—what continues, endures, or accompanies you. English says 'I have'; Spanish asks, 'Do you hold it, or have you carried it this long?'"
    },
    {
      "phase": "system_logic",
      "line": "**1️⃣ TENER → To have, to possess, to experience, or to express age and conditions.**\nFrom Latin *tenere* (to hold, to keep), it implies ownership, possession, or an internal state.\n- *Tengo un coche.* (I have a car.)\n- *Tengo hambre / frío / sueño.* (I’m hungry / cold / sleepy.)\n- *Tengo veinte años.* (I’m twenty years old.)\n- *Tengo que estudiar.* (I have to study.)\nUsed for conditions, needs, or permanent possession.\n\n**2️⃣ LLEVAR → To carry, wear, or indicate how long something has been happening.**\nFrom Latin *levare* (to carry upward), it adds the idea of ongoing motion or burden.\n- *Llevo gafas.* (I wear glasses.)\n- *Llevamos tres años juntos.* (We’ve been together for three years.)\n- *Lleva barba.* (He has a beard / wears a beard.)\n- *Llevo mucho tiempo esperando.* (I’ve been waiting a long time.)\n\n**3️⃣ Core contrast:**\n| Function | Verb | Focus |\n|-----------|------|--------|\n| Possession / internal state | tener | what you have |\n| Duration / external condition | llevar | what you carry |\n\n**4️⃣ Idioms and nuances:**\n- *Tener razón* (to be right), *tener prisa* (to be in a hurry), *tener suerte* (to be lucky).\n- *Llevar bien / mal algo* (to handle something well / badly): 'No llevo bien el calor.' (I don’t handle heat well.)\n- *Llevarse* (reflexive) means 'to get along' or 'to take with oneself.'\n\nIn short, *tener* defines possession; *llevar* measures endurance. One holds, the other bears."
    },
    {
      "phase": "meaning_depth",
      "origin": "Tener and llevar descend from Latin roots *tenere* ('to hold') and *levare* ('to lift or carry'), preserving the dual sense of grasping and bearing through time.",
      "story": "In ancient Latin, *tenere* meant to hold tightly—to possess, to keep safe. *Levāre* meant to lift or raise—to carry a thing forward. Spanish kept both, building a language that distinguishes stability from motion. *Tener* grounds you; *llevar* moves you.\n\nThis distinction reveals Spanish sensitivity to time and weight. *Tener* is static—you possess hunger. *Llevar* is dynamic—you’ve been carrying that hunger all day. The verbs trace a philosophical difference between what belongs to you and what happens with you.\n\nCulturally, *llevar* often appears where English uses have been, making it an emotional timeline: 'Llevo semanas pensando en eso' (I’ve been thinking about that for weeks). The word imagines life as something carried rather than endured. *Tener* remains matter-of-fact—it describes, names, defines. *Llevar* humanizes, giving continuity a heartbeat.\n\nWriters use the contrast to mark inner versus outer possession. A character may *tener miedo* (feel fear) or *llevar años con miedo* (live years carrying fear). The first moment is felt; the second is lived. Spanish grammar refuses to confuse holding with enduring.",
      "wrap_line": "Tener and llevar balance stillness and motion—grammar that separates what we have from what we’ve carried along the way."
    },
