  "id": "mmspanish__lesson_B1_115_ir_vs_venir",
  "title": "B1.115 Ir vs. Venir — The Grammar of Motion and Perspective",
  "mode": "mix_method",
  "steps": [
    {
      "phase": "english_anchor",
      "line": "In English, we use go and come to show direction: I go there, Come here. Spanish mirrors this distinction with **ir** and **venir**, but adds a deeper layer—**point of reference**. English does this through context; Spanish encodes it through relationship. **Ir** means to go away from the current or implied location, while **venir** means to come toward the speaker or listener. The difference isn’t about distance—it’s about perspective. Spanish doesn’t ask where something moves; it asks where you stand when it moves."
    },
    {
      "phase": "system_logic",
      "line": "**1️⃣ IR → To go, to move away from the speaker or reference point.**\nFocuses on departure, distance, and intention.\n- *Voy al trabajo a las ocho.* (I go to work at eight.)\n- *Fuimos a la playa.* (We went to the beach.)\n- *¿Vas a venir?* (Are you going to come?) — even here, *ir* marks departure before movement toward.\n\n**2️⃣ VENIR → To come, to move toward the speaker or reference point.**\nFocuses on arrival, proximity, and convergence.\n- *Ven aquí.* (Come here.)\n- *Mis amigos vienen a mi casa.* (My friends are coming to my house.)\n- *¿Cuándo vas a venir?* (When will you come?)\n\n**3️⃣ Perspective rule:**\n| Direction | Verb | Reference |\n|------------|------|-------------|\n| Away from here | ir | moving outward |\n| Toward here | venir | moving inward |\n\n**4️⃣ Compound and reflexive uses:**\n- *Irse* = to leave / to go away: 'Me voy ahora.' (I’m leaving now.)\n- *Venirse abajo* = to collapse emotionally or physically: 'Se vino abajo la pared.' (The wall came down.)\n- *Ir + a + infinitive* = near future: 'Voy a estudiar.' (I’m going to study.)\n- *Venir + gerundio* = progressive background: 'Viene diciendo lo mismo.' (He’s been saying the same thing.)\n\n**5️⃣ Nuance:** English frames movement from the speaker’s point of view. Spanish, however, adjusts dynamically—it follows emotional, spatial, or conversational perspective. If you’re not home but speaking of someone arriving there, you still say *venir*: 'Mis padres vienen mañana'—they’re coming (to where *you* emotionally belong)."
    },
    {
      "phase": "meaning_depth",
      "origin": "Ir and venir both descend from Latin: *ire* (to go) and *venire* (to come). Their contrast in Spanish preserved the Roman idea of movement as dialogue—departure and return bound together.",
      "story": "The Romans imagined life as two directions—*ire* (to go toward destiny) and *venire* (to come into presence). Spanish inherited this dual motion but humanized it. *Ir* marks intention; *venir* marks connection. One carries the will to move; the other, the welcome of arrival.\n\nCulturally, this difference runs deep. Spanish speakers instinctively anchor verbs of movement to empathy. You say *ven* (come) when you’re inviting someone into your space or care. You say *ve* (go) when you’re sending them toward purpose or freedom. The verbs carry emotional geography: distance isn’t just spatial—it’s relational.\n\nIn literature, *venir* suggests intimacy and reunion. 'Ven conmigo' (Come with me) carries warmth and protection. *Ir* evokes search, exile, or ambition: 'Voy a buscar mi destino.' Together, they outline human experience—the pull between leaving and belonging. Grammar becomes compass, pointing toward motion not just in space but in feeling.",
      "wrap_line": "Ir and venir are Spanish movement made human—grammar that knows every journey is also an invitation or a farewell."
