  "mode": "mix_method",
  "steps": [
    {
      "phase": "english_anchor",
      "line": "In English, we use leave for both exiting and releasing: I left the house, I left my job, I left him. Spanish divides this into two powerful verbs—**salir** and **dejar**—because it distinguishes between motion and decision. English does this with tone; Spanish does it with agency. **Salir** means to go out or exit—a physical or situational departure. **Dejar** means to leave something behind—to let go, to abandon, to permit. One moves your body; the other moves your will. English calls both leaving; Spanish knows the difference between walking away and giving away."
    },
    {
      "phase": "system_logic",
      "line": "**1️⃣ SALIR → To go out, to leave (a place), to depart.**\nFrom Latin *salire* (to jump or leap), it implies motion outward or forward.\n- *Salgo de casa a las siete.* (I leave the house at seven.)\n- *Salimos del trabajo temprano.* (We left work early.)\n- *¿Quieres salir esta noche?* (Do you want to go out tonight?)\n**Key pattern:** *salir de + place* marks physical departure.\n\n**2️⃣ DEJAR → To leave behind, to let, to allow, to stop doing something.**\nFrom Latin *de- + laxare* (to loosen, release), it implies separation or relinquishment.\n- *Dejé las llaves en la mesa.* (I left the keys on the table.)\n- *Dejó el trabajo el año pasado.* (He left his job last year.)\n- *Déjame en paz.* (Leave me alone.)\n- *Dejar de + infinitive* → to stop doing something: *Dejé de fumar.* (I stopped smoking.)\n\n**3️⃣ Contrast summary:**\n| Function | Verb | Type of leaving |\n|-----------|------|----------------|\n| To exit or move outward | salir | physical / external |\n| To leave something behind | dejar | emotional / intentional |\n\n**4️⃣ Reflexive and idiomatic uses:**\n- *Salirse de control* → to get out of control.\n- *Dejarse llevar* → to let oneself go, to go with the flow.\n- *Dejar caer* → to drop (literally or metaphorically).\n\n**5️⃣ Emotional nuance:**\n- *Salir* is neutral, spatial, forward. It’s a door opening.\n- *Dejar* carries emotional gravity—loss, permission, or detachment. It’s the moment after the door closes."
    },
