  "id": "mmspanish__lesson_B1_118_esperar_vs_esperarse",
  "title": "B1.118 Esperar vs. Esperarse — The Grammar of Expectation and Surprise",
  "mode": "mix_method",
  "steps": [
    {
      "phase": "english_anchor",
      "line": "In English, we use wait and expect for different shades of patience: I’m waiting for you, I expect you to call, I didn’t expect that. Spanish expresses both ideas through one root—**esperar**—but changes meaning through reflection: **esperar** and **esperarse**. English does this with separate verbs; Spanish does it with point of view. **Esperar** looks outward, expecting something from the world. **Esperarse** looks inward, bracing for what might happen. The reflexive form folds emotion back onto the speaker—grammar transforming waiting into wondering."
    },
    {
      "phase": "system_logic",
      "line": "**1️⃣ ESPERAR → To wait, to hope, to expect (externally focused).**\nFrom Latin *sperare* (to hope), it expresses patience or trust directed outward.\n- *Espero el autobús.* (I’m waiting for the bus.)\n- *Espero que vengas.* (I hope you come.)\n- *Esperan una respuesta.* (They’re waiting for an answer.)\n\n**Uses:**\n- *Esperar + noun* → to wait for something: 'Espero el tren.'\n- *Esperar + que + subjunctive* → to hope or wish: 'Espero que estés bien.'\n- *Esperar + infinitive* → to expect to do something: 'Espero llegar temprano.'\n\n**2️⃣ ESPERARSE → To expect, to anticipate, to be prepared for something (internally focused).**\nReflexive use adds surprise, acceptance, or resignation.\n- *No me lo esperaba.* (I didn’t expect it.)\n- *Me esperaba algo peor.* (I expected something worse.)\n- *¿Te esperabas eso?* (Did you see that coming?)\n\n**Contrast summary:**\n| Function | Verb | Focus |\n|-----------|------|--------|\n| To wait / to hope | esperar | external expectation |\n| To expect / to anticipate | esperarse | internal reaction |\n\n**Idiomatic extensions:**\n- *Esperar lo inesperado* → to expect the unexpected.\n- *Más vale esperar que lamentar* → better to wait than regret.\n- *No era lo que me esperaba* → it wasn’t what I was expecting.\n\n*Esperar* belongs to patience; *esperarse* belongs to perspective."
