  "id": "mmspanish__lesson_B1_121_poder_vs_saber",
  "title": "B1.121 Poder vs. Saber — The Grammar of Ability and Possibility",
  "mode": "mix_method",
  "steps": [
    {
      "phase": "english_anchor",
      "line": "In English, we use can or be able to both for permission and ability: I can swim, Can I go out?, I could hear you. Spanish separates this idea into **poder** and **saber**, because it distinguishes **capacity** from **competence**. English does this with tone; Spanish does it with logic. **Poder** expresses possibility, permission, or physical ability in a given moment. **Saber** expresses learned skill or knowledge. English lets can mean both knowing how and being allowed to; Spanish insists on choosing—between what you know and what you’re allowed to do."
    },
    {
      "phase": "system_logic",
      "line": "**1️⃣ PODER → To be able to, can, may.**\nFrom Latin *posse* (to be capable), it expresses external or situational power.\n- *Puedo ir al baño.* (Can I go to the bathroom?) → permission.\n- *No puedo levantar esto.* (I can’t lift this.) → physical ability.\n- *Podemos ayudarte.* (We can help you.) → potential or offer.\n\n**Modal shades:**\n- **Possibility:** *Puede llover.* (It may rain.)\n- **Permission:** *¿Puedo salir?* (Can I go out?)\n- **Capability:** *No puedo conducir sin gafas.* (I can’t drive without glasses.)\n\n**2️⃣ SABER → To know how (skill through learning).**\nFrom Latin *sapere* (to have taste, to know by experience). Expresses acquired ability or knowledge.\n- *Sé nadar.* (I know how to swim.)\n- *¿Sabes tocar la guitarra?* (Do you know how to play the guitar?)\n- *No sabe mentir.* (He doesn’t know how to lie.)\n\n**3️⃣ Core difference:**\n| Meaning | Verb | Focus |\n|----------|------|--------|\n| Capacity, permission, opportunity | poder | situational power |\n| Learned ability or skill | saber | acquired competence |\n\n**4️⃣ Reflexive and idiomatic uses:**\n- *Poderse* adds emotion or limit: 'No me puedo más.' (I can’t take it anymore.)\n- *A más no poder* → 'as much as possible.'\n- *Saber de memoria* → to know by heart.\n\n**Mnemonic:** If it depends on **circumstance**, use *poder.* If it depends on **training**, use *saber.*"
