      "story": "In ancient Latin, power and knowledge were siblings—*posse* ruled the body, *sapere* ruled the mind. Spanish kept that lineage intact but divided their territory. *Poder* measures strength or permission; *saber* measures understanding. The language treats capacity and competence not as synonyms, but as two ways of moving through the world.\n\n*Culturally,* Spanish favors precision in agency. To *poder* is to have means; to *saber* is to have mastery. 'Puedo bailar' means you’re free or capable to dance; 'sé bailar' means you’ve learned how. Grammar demands honesty about what kind of 'can' you mean.\n\nThis distinction gives speech subtlety. *No puedo hacerlo* might imply fatigue or circumstance. *No sé hacerlo* confesses lack of knowledge. One limits the moment; the other limits the self. Spanish speakers feel this difference instinctively—it’s how the language respects both freedom and humility.\n\nWriters use the two verbs to frame character. *Poder* defines potential and restraint—what the world allows. *Saber* defines wisdom and growth—what time teaches. In conversation, both verbs trace humanity’s two powers: strength and understanding.",
      "wrap_line": "Poder and saber give ability two meanings—grammar that separates what you can do from what you have learned to do."
