  "id": "mmspanish__lesson_B1_122_hacer_vs_realizar",
  "title": "B1.122 Hacer vs. Realizar — The Grammar of Doing and Achieving",
  "mode": "mix_method",
  "steps": [
    {
      "phase": "english_anchor",
      "line": "In English, we use do and make to express action and creation: I did my work, She made a plan. Spanish uses **hacer** for both but introduces another layer—**realizar**—to describe accomplished, purposeful, or completed actions. English does this through context; Spanish does it through hierarchy. **Hacer** is about performing, executing, or producing; **realizar** is about fulfilling, achieving, or carrying out something meaningful. English says do it; Spanish asks whether you simply did it, or truly made it real."
    },
    {
      "phase": "system_logic",
      "line": "**1️⃣ HACER → To do, to make, to act.**\nFrom Latin *facere* (to make, to build), *hacer* is the universal verb of action and creation.\n- *Hago mi tarea.* (I do my homework.)\n- *Hicimos una torta.* (We made a cake.)\n- *¿Qué haces?* (What are you doing?)\n\n**Key uses:**\n- *Hacer + noun* → to perform or produce: *hacer ejercicio* (do exercise), *hacer ruido* (make noise).\n- *Hacer + weather expressions* → *hace frío / hace sol / hace viento.*\n- *Hacer de + role* → to play the part of: *Hizo de guía.* (He acted as a guide.)\n\n**2️⃣ REALIZAR → To carry out, to achieve, to fulfill.**\nFrom Latin *realis* (real) + *-izare* (to make), it literally means 'to make real.'\n- *Realizó sus sueños.* (She fulfilled her dreams.)\n- *Estamos realizando un proyecto.* (We are carrying out a project.)\n- *Se realizó como artista.* (She realized herself as an artist.)\n\n**3️⃣ Difference in focus:**\n| Function | Verb | Focus |\n|-----------|------|--------|\n| Action / activity | hacer | physical or generic action |\n| Fulfillment / completion | realizar | purposeful or formal accomplishment |\n\n**4️⃣ Idioms and contexts:**\n- *Hacer caso* → to pay attention.\n- *Hacer daño* → to harm or hurt.\n- *Hacer falta* → to be necessary / needed.\n- *Realizar un sueño* → to make a dream come true.\n- *Realizar una prueba / entrevista* → to conduct or complete something official.\n\n**Mnemonic:** *Hacer* does; *realizar* achieves."
    },
    {
      "phase": "meaning_depth",
