      "story": "In Latin, *facere* was creation itself—to act, to shape, to forge. *Realis* meant 'of the thing itself.' Spanish merged them but preserved their moral distance. *Hacer* is the act; *realizar* is the result. You can *hacer un trabajo* and still not *realizarte* in it—one completes the task, the other fulfills the person.\n\nThis distinction gives Spanish its emotional precision around purpose. *Hacer* belongs to routine, to tasks and gestures. *Realizar* belongs to destiny, to effort finding meaning. The same word that in English feels bureaucratic—'to carry out'—in Spanish feels intimate, even existential: *Realizó su sueño de viajar por el mundo.* Grammar becomes aspiration.\n\nIn everyday speech, *hacer* is neutral and omnipresent, the engine of conversation. *Realizar* adds weight, formality, or reflection. Scientists *realizan experimentos*, artists *se realizan creando*. The difference isn’t about difficulty—it’s about depth.\n\nWriters use *realizar* to elevate experience: 'Me realicé al perdonar.' It transforms accomplishment into awakening. *Hacer* describes what you do; *realizar* defines why you did it. The verbs mirror Spanish respect for both labor and purpose—the work itself, and the truth it reveals.",
      "wrap_line": "Hacer and realizar give Spanish action two souls—grammar that separates the doing from the becoming real."
