  "id": "mmspanish__lesson_B1_132_ir_gerund",
  "title": "B1.132 Ir + Gerund — Progression in Motion",
  "mode": "mix_method",
  "steps": [
    {
      "phase": "english_anchor",
      "line": "In English, we express gradual or developing actions with phrases like 'little by little,' 'bit by bit,' or 'kept on doing.' We say, 'He’s getting better,' or 'She’s improving slowly.' Spanish captures this sense of **ongoing progress** with the structure **ir + gerund**, literally 'to go doing.' Instead of describing the process with an adverb, Spanish uses motion to show time unfolding. The action doesn’t just continue—it advances. English does this by adding descriptive words of degree; Spanish does it by making movement part of the grammar."
    },
    {
      "phase": "system_logic",
      "line": "**1️⃣ Structure and Meaning.**\nFormula: *ir (conjugated) + gerund* → 'to be gradually doing something.'\n\n**Examples:**\n- *Voy aprendiendo más cada día.* (I’m gradually learning more each day.)\n- *Van mejorando las cosas.* (Things are getting better.)\n- *Iba entendiendo poco a poco.* (I was starting to understand little by little.)\n\nHere, *ir* acts as a **progressive auxiliary**—a helper that tracks slow movement through time. It’s not about location but **direction of change**.\n\n**2️⃣ Grammar behavior.**\n| Tense | Function | Example |\n|--------|-----------|----------|\n| Present | gradual development now | *Voy recordando más.* (I’m remembering more.) |\n| Preterite / Imperfect | progressive change in the past | *Iba sintiendo frío.* (I was starting to feel cold.) |\n| Future | slow upcoming change | *Iré entendiendo.* (I’ll gradually understand.) |\n\n**3️⃣ Contrast with other progressives:**\n- *Estar + gerund* = ongoing action in the present moment. (*Estoy estudiando* → I’m studying now.)\n- *Ir + gerund* = ongoing action with progression or accumulation. (*Voy estudiando más cada día* → I’m studying more and more.)\n\n**4️⃣ Common modifiers:**\nOften paired with phrases like *poco a poco*, *cada vez más*, *lentamente*, which reinforce gradualness.\n\n**5️⃣ Exceptions and rhythm:**\nAvoid *ir + gerund* when the action doesn’t imply growth or sequence. *Voy comiendo* sounds strange unless describing steady eating over time. This structure prefers verbs that evolve—learning, improving, recovering.\n\n**Summary:**\nSpanish uses *ir + gerund* to show **accumulating change**, turning slow progress into visible movement. Grammar becomes a motion picture of improvement."
