  "id": "mmspanish__lesson_B1_134_tener_que_vs_haber_que",
  "title": "B1.134 Tener que vs. Haber que — Personal vs. Impersonal Obligation",
  "mode": "mix_method",
  "steps": [
    {
      "phase": "english_anchor",
      "line": "In English, we express duty or necessity with must, have to, or need to. We say, 'I have to go,' or 'One must be careful.' Spanish divides these ideas by **who feels the obligation**. **Tener que + infinitive** is personal—it attaches the duty to someone specific: *tengo que estudiar* (I have to study). **Haber que + infinitive**, especially in the form *hay que*, is impersonal—it speaks about what needs to be done in general: *hay que estudiar* (one must study). English does this by tone and context; Spanish does it by grammar—deciding whether responsibility belongs to a person or to everyone."
    },
    {
      "phase": "system_logic",
      "line": "**1️⃣ TENER QUE + INFINITIVE → Personal necessity.**\nFormula: *tener (conjugated) + que + infinitive.*\nUsed when the speaker names who must act.\n- *Tengo que trabajar mañana.* (I have to work tomorrow.)\n- *Tienes que venir conmigo.* (You have to come with me.)\n- *Tenemos que estudiar más.* (We have to study more.)\n\n**2️⃣ HABER QUE + INFINITIVE → General or impersonal necessity.**\nUsually appears as *hay que + infinitive* (present tense of *haber*).\n- *Hay que comer bien.* (It’s necessary to eat well.)\n- *Hay que respetar las reglas.* (One must respect the rules.)\n- *Había que salir temprano.* (It was necessary to leave early.)\nThis structure has **no subject**—the obligation exists, but nobody is directly named.\n\n**3️⃣ Comparison Table:**\n| Type of Obligation | Structure | Example | Meaning |\n|---------------------|------------|----------|----------|\n| Personal | tener que + infinitive | *Tengo que ayudar.* | I have to help. |\n| Impersonal | haber que + infinitive | *Hay que ayudar.* | One must help. |\n\n**4️⃣ Placement and Agreement.**\n*Tener* conjugates to match the subject: *tengo, tienes, tiene, tenemos, tienen.* *Haber* does not—it stays fixed as *hay que* unless moved to another tense (*había que, habrá que*). Pronouns and negation go before the verb: *No tienes que ir* (You don’t have to go), *No hay que correr* (We shouldn’t run).\n\n**5️⃣ Exceptions and nuance.**\n- *Tener que* carries emotion—it feels personal or pressured. *Tengo que contarte algo* hints at something important or secret.\n- *Hay que* feels objective or moral—something everyone knows must be done.\nSpanish doesn’t just say what must happen; it shows who bears the weight."
    },
