      "phase": "meaning_depth",
      "origin": "From Latin *tenere* ('to hold') and *habere* ('to have'), the two verbs diverged—*tener* for possession and control, *haber* for existence and necessity.",
      "story": "Every culture defines responsibility differently, and Spanish captures that distinction in grammar itself. *Tener que* holds obligation in the hands—it’s something you personally carry. *Haber que* lets it float in the air, a truth without owner. Together they show how language measures duty by proximity.\n\nA mother might sigh, *hay que levantarse temprano*, meaning the household must rise—it’s law of the day. But when she turns to her son and says, *tienes que levantarte*, the command finds a target. The first breath is universal; the second is directed. Spanish gives voice to both kinds of weight: social and personal.\n\nIn literature and song, this contrast becomes moral tone. *Hay que luchar por la vida* (one must fight for life) sounds philosophical, even communal. *Tengo que luchar por mi vida* (I have to fight for my life) becomes survival, intimate and raw. The difference between *hay* and *tengo* is the distance between destiny and decision.\n\nGrammatically, this split teaches perspective: where English blurs the line between moral and personal must, Spanish insists on precision. Obligation in Spanish always has a direction—it either lands on someone or fills the room like air.",
      "wrap_line": "To say *hay que* is to name a truth; to say *tengo que* is to shoulder it."
