  "id": "mmspanish__lesson_B1_139_llevar_past_participle",
  "title": "B1.139 Llevar + Past Participle — Duration and Completion",
  "mode": "mix_method",
  "steps": [
    {
      "phase": "english_anchor",
      "line": "In English, we describe how long something has been going on or how far we’ve come with phrases like 'I’ve been studying for two years' or 'I already have three done.' Spanish can express this same sense of **ongoing progress toward completion** with **llevar + past participle**. Literally, *llevar* means 'to carry,' so this structure shows what someone has been 'carrying along'—the amount or stage of an action so far. English does this with perfect tenses and time markers; Spanish does it by turning progress into something you physically bear, a load you’ve carried through time."
    },
    {
      "phase": "system_logic",
      "line": "**1️⃣ LLEVAR + PAST PARTICIPLE → To have done or completed something up to a certain point.**\nFormula: *llevar (conjugated) + past participle / quantity / time phrase.*\n- *Llevo estudiado medio libro.* (I’ve read half the book so far.)\n- *Llevamos recorridos veinte kilómetros.* (We’ve covered twenty kilometers.)\n- *Llevas gastado mucho dinero.* (You’ve spent a lot of money.)\n\n**2️⃣ Function:**\nThis structure highlights **partial completion**—an action in progress but already carrying measurable results. The verb *llevar* measures accumulated effort.\n\n**3️⃣ Grammar pattern:**\n| Subject | Llevar (present) | Example |\n|----------|------------------|----------|\n| yo | llevo | llevo vivido mucho |\n| tú | llevas | llevas ahorrado bastante |\n| él/ella | lleva | lleva ganado experiencia |\n| nosotros | llevamos | llevamos hecho la mitad |\n| ellos | llevan | llevan trabajado años |\n\n**4️⃣ Placement and agreement:**\n- The **past participle** agrees in gender and number with the **object**, not the subject. Example: *Llevamos hechas las tareas* (We have the tasks done.)\n- Pronouns and negation precede *llevar*: *No llevo leído nada hoy.* (I haven’t read anything today.)\n\n**5️⃣ Contrast with other structures:**\n- *He leído* → I have read (focuses on completion).\n- *Llevo leído* → I have read (focuses on **amount or duration**).\nSpanish turns abstract time into something tactile—you’re literally carrying your progress.\n\n**6️⃣ Idiomatic uses:**\n- *Llevar + gerund* (to have been doing something) → *Llevo estudiando tres horas.* (I’ve been studying for three hours.)\n- *Llevar + adjective/past participle* (to carry a result) → *Llevo cansado todo el día.* (I’ve been tired all day.)"
