{
  "id": "mmspanish__lesson_B1_148_future_simple",
  "title": "B1.148 Future Simple — Predicting and Promising",
  "mode": "mix_method",
  "steps": [
    {
      "phase": "english_anchor",
      "line": "In English, we use 'will' or 'shall' to talk about what’s going to happen: 'I will call you,' 'It will rain,' 'We shall see.' Spanish does this with the **future simple tense**, formed by attaching endings directly to the infinitive: *hablaré, comerás, vivirán.* But Spanish doesn’t stop at prediction—it uses this tense to express **certainty, intent, and even emotional distance.** English builds the future with helper words; Spanish builds it into the verb itself, turning time into a promise."
    },
    {
      "phase": "system_logic",
      "line": "**1️⃣ Construction:**\nFormula: *infinitive + future ending.*\nEndings (same for all verbs):\n| Subject | Ending | Example (hablar) |\n|----------|----------|------------------|\n| yo | -é | hablaré |\n| tú | -ás | hablarás |\n| él/ella/usted | -á | hablará |\n| nosotros | -emos | hablaremos |\n| vosotros | -éis | hablaréis |\n| ellos/ustedes | -án | hablarán |\n\n**2️⃣ Irregular stems:**\nSome verbs change their base but keep the same endings:\n- *tener → tendré*\n- *salir → saldré*\n- *decir → diré*\n- *hacer → haré*\n- *venir → vendré*\n- *poder → podré*\n\n**3️⃣ Meaning and use:**\nThe future tense in Spanish carries four main functions:\n1. **Prediction:** *Mañana lloverá.* (It will rain tomorrow.)\n2. **Promise or determination:** *Te llamaré esta noche.* (I’ll call you tonight.)\n3. **Uncertainty or probability (in present time):** *Estará en casa.* (He’s probably at home.)\n4. **Formality or distance:** *Usted sabrá qué hacer.* (You’ll know what to do.)\n\n**4️⃣ Comparison with 'ir a + infinitive':**\n- *Voy a estudiar* = I’m going to study (planned future).\n- *Estudiaré* = I will study (definite or solemn future).\nThe *simple future* feels firmer and more declarative—it’s the grammar of intent, not mere expectation.\n\n**5️⃣ Notes and rhythm:**\nSpanish attaches future endings directly to the infinitive, merging what is and what will be. The structure is clean, rhythmic, and final, like a drumbeat marking certainty."
    },
    {
      "phase": "meaning_depth",
      "origin": "From Latin’s periphrastic future ('amare habeo' → 'I have to love'), Spanish fused the helper verb *haber* with infinitives, creating a single-word future.",
      "story": "Spanish treats the future as an act of faith. The endings come from ancient phrases that once meant 'I have to'—so when you say *haré*, you’re not just predicting, you’re committing. It’s a small, inherited echo of promise.\n\nIn daily life, Spanish speakers use the future not only to tell what will happen, but also to guess, reassure, or wonder. *Estará durmiendo* doesn’t mean 'he will be sleeping'—it means 'he’s probably asleep.' Grammar becomes intuition. The future tense listens to tone as much as time.\n\nIn love, *te amaré* sounds eternal; in argument, *ya verás* (you’ll see) sounds sharp. The same tense stretches from tenderness to warning. Because Spanish gives emotion to grammar, the future doesn’t just describe—it declares. Each ending—*é, ás, á*—is a note of conviction.\n\nEven poets feel this difference. When Neruda writes *algún día sabrás por qué te amo*, he’s not simply predicting knowledge; he’s promising revelation. The Spanish future always points toward destiny, never neutrality.",
      "wrap_line": "The future tense in Spanish is the grammar of belief—each word a small vow spoken forward in time."
    },
    {
