  "id": "mmspanish__lesson_B1_150_conditional_simple",
  "title": "B1.150 Conditional Simple — The Grammar of Hypothesis",
  "mode": "mix_method",
  "steps": [
    {
      "phase": "english_anchor",
      "line": "In English, we use 'would' to imagine, soften, or speculate: 'I would go,' 'She would help you,' 'It would be nice.' Spanish expresses these same ideas through the **conditional simple tense**—the verb endings *-ía, -ías, -ía, -íamos, -íais, -ían* added to the infinitive. It’s used for **politeness, possibility, and unreal situations.** English does this by adding 'would' before a verb; Spanish does it by building that 'would' directly into the word itself."
    },
    {
      "phase": "system_logic",
      "line": "**1️⃣ Construction:**\nFormula: *infinitive + conditional endings.*\n| Subject | Ending | Example (hablar) |\n|----------|---------|------------------|\n| yo | -ía | hablaría |\n| tú | -ías | hablarías |\n| él/ella/usted | -ía | hablaría |\n| nosotros | -íamos | hablaríamos |\n| vosotros | -íais | hablaríais |\n| ellos/ustedes | -ían | hablarían |\n\n**2️⃣ Irregular stems:**\nThe same verbs that are irregular in the future are also irregular here:\n- *tener → tendría*\n- *decir → diría*\n- *hacer → haría*\n- *poder → podría*\n- *venir → vendría*\n- *poner → pondría*\n\n**3️⃣ Main uses:**\n1. **Politeness or soft tone:** *¿Podrías ayudarme?* (Could you help me?)\n2. **Hypothetical situations:** *Iría contigo si tuviera tiempo.* (I would go with you if I had time.)\n3. **Future in the past:** *Dijo que llegaría a las ocho.* (He said he would arrive at eight.)\n4. **Probability in the past:** *Serían las cinco.* (It was probably around five.)\n\n**4️⃣ Placement and combinations:**\nConditional verbs can appear alone or in *si* (if) clauses:\n- *Si tuviera dinero, viajaría más.* (If I had money, I’d travel more.)\nIn these structures, the verb in the *si* clause usually takes the **imperfect subjunctive**, while the main clause takes the **conditional simple.**\n\n**5️⃣ Tone and nuance:**\nUnlike English 'would,' the Spanish conditional often sounds gentler or more respectful. *Quisiera hablar contigo* (I would like to speak with you) feels warmer than *quiero hablar contigo.* It softens intent through grammar rather than apology."
