  "id": "mmspanish__lesson_B1_151_conditional_perfect",
  "title": "B1.151 Conditional Perfect — The Grammar of Regret",
  "mode": "mix_method",
  "steps": [
    {
      "phase": "english_anchor",
      "line": "In English, we use 'would have' to describe something that didn’t happen but could have: 'I would have gone,' 'She would have called,' 'They would have helped.' Spanish expresses the same sense of missed possibility with the **conditional perfect tense**—*haber* in the conditional + a past participle (*habría ido, habrías llamado, habrían ayudado*). English builds the regret by adding 'would have'; Spanish does it by turning *haber*—'to have'—into a doorway to what almost was."
    },
    {
      "phase": "system_logic",
      "line": "**1️⃣ Structure:**\nFormula: *haber (conditional) + past participle.*\n| Subject | Haber (conditional) | Example (viajar) |\n|----------|--------------------|------------------|\n| yo | habría | habría viajado |\n| tú | habrías | habrías viajado |\n| él/ella/usted | habría | habría viajado |\n| nosotros | habríamos | habríamos viajado |\n| vosotros | habríais | habríais viajado |\n| ellos/ustedes | habrían | habrían viajado |\n\n**2️⃣ Meaning:**\nThe **conditional perfect** imagines a past that didn’t happen. It’s used for:\n1. **Hypothetical pasts:** *Habría ido contigo si me hubieras invitado.* (I would have gone if you had invited me.)\n2. **Regret or reflection:** *Habría sido mejor esperar.* (It would have been better to wait.)\n3. **Probability about the past:** *Habría llegado tarde.* (He must have arrived late.)\n\n**3️⃣ Connection with 'si' clauses:**\nUsed after *si + pluperfect subjunctive* to describe impossible past conditions:\n- *Si hubiera estudiado, habría aprobado.* (If I had studied, I would have passed.)\nThis pairing forms the backbone of Spanish hypothetical storytelling.\n\n**4️⃣ Placement:**\nNegative and pronoun placement stay consistent: *No me habría ido* (I wouldn’t have left), *Se lo habría dicho* (I would have told him/her). The structure always keeps *haber* directly before the participle.\n\n**5️⃣ Common mistake:**\nDon’t confuse *habría* (conditional) with *había* (imperfect). *Habría comido* = I would have eaten. *Había comido* = I had eaten. One looks back at possibility; the other, at fact."
