{
  "id": "mmspanish__lesson_B1_152_imperfect_subjunctive",
  "title": "B1.152 Imperfect Subjunctive — The Grammar of Unreality",
  "mode": "mix_method",
  "steps": [
    {
      "phase": "english_anchor",
      "line": "In English, we hint at unreality or doubt with words like 'if,' 'were,' or 'would': 'If I were rich,' 'I wish she came,' 'I hoped he’d call.' Spanish has a dedicated tense for these imagined or uncertain moments—the **imperfect subjunctive.** It’s used in dependent clauses after certain verbs, when the action is uncertain, unreal, or emotionally charged. English does this with helper words and tone; Spanish does it by changing the verb itself, turning feeling and possibility into grammar."
    },
    {
      "phase": "system_logic",
      "line": "**1️⃣ Formation:**\nStart with the **preterite plural form** of the verb, drop the *-ron*, and add these endings:\n| Subject | Ending | Example (hablar) |\n|----------|---------|------------------|\n| yo | -ra | hablara |\n| tú | -ras | hablaras |\n| él/ella/usted | -ra | hablara |\n| nosotros | -ramos | habláramos (accent before ending) |\n| vosotros | -rais | hablarais |\n| ellos/ustedes | -ran | hablaran |\n\nAlternate form with *-se* endings (*hablase, comiese*) is also correct but more formal or literary.\n\n**2️⃣ When to use it:**\n- After past-tense triggers of emotion, doubt, or desire:\n  - *Quería que vinieras.* (I wanted you to come.)\n  - *Dudaba que lloviera.* (I doubted it rained.)\n- In *si* (if) clauses describing unreal conditions:\n  - *Si tuviera dinero, viajaría.* (If I had money, I would travel.)\n- After *como si* (as if): *Actuó como si no me conociera.* (He acted as if he didn’t know me.)\n\n**3️⃣ Trigger verbs and phrases:**\n- Desire: *querer que, esperar que*\n- Doubt: *dudar que, no creer que*\n- Emotion: *alegrarse de que, temer que*\n- Hypotheticals: *si + imperfect subjunctive + conditional*\n\n**4️⃣ Quick contrast:**\n| Situation | Tense | Example |\n|------------|--------|----------|\n| Real past | indicative | *Sabía que vino.* (I knew he came.) |\n| Imagined past | subjunctive | *Quería que viniera.* (I wanted him to come.) |\n\nSpanish separates what happened from what was hoped for, preserving emotion through structure."
    },
