  "id": "mmspanish__lesson_B1_153_pluperfect_subjunctive",
  "title": "B1.153 Pluperfect Subjunctive — The Grammar of “Would Have”",
  "mode": "mix_method",
  "steps": [
    {
      "phase": "english_anchor",
      "line": "In English, we say 'if I had known,' 'if she had gone,' or 'I wish you had called' to talk about impossible pasts—things that could have happened but didn’t. Spanish expresses this with the **pluperfect subjunctive**, formed by combining *haber* in its past subjunctive form with a past participle: *hubiera/hubiese + participle.* English builds this feeling with helper verbs; Spanish does it by bending grammar into a mirror of regret, where possibility and loss coexist in one verb phrase."
    },
    {
      "phase": "system_logic",
      "line": "**1️⃣ Structure:**\nFormula: *haber (imperfect subjunctive) + past participle.*\n| Subject | Haber (subjunctive) | Example (comer) |\n|----------|---------------------|------------------|\n| yo | hubiera / hubiese | hubiera comido |\n| tú | hubieras / hubieses | hubieras comido |\n| él/ella/usted | hubiera / hubiese | hubiera comido |\n| nosotros | hubiéramos / hubiésemos | hubiéramos comido |\n| vosotros | hubierais / hubieseis | hubierais comido |\n| ellos/ustedes | hubieran / hubiesen | hubieran comido |\n\n**2️⃣ Hubiera vs. Hubiese:** Both forms are correct and interchangeable; *hubiera* is more common in modern speech, while *hubiese* appears in formal writing or older literature.\n\n**3️⃣ Common uses:**\n1. **In “if” (si) clauses for impossible pasts:**\n   - *Si hubiera sabido, habría venido.* (If I had known, I would have come.)\n2. **After verbs expressing emotion or doubt about the past:**\n   - *Ojalá que hubieras estado allí.* (I wish you had been there.)\n3. **Reported speech or indirect past desires:**\n   - *Esperaba que hubieran terminado.* (I hoped they had finished.)\n\n**4️⃣ The classic pairing:**\n- *Si + pluperfect subjunctive → habría + participle.*\n  - *Si hubiera estudiado más, habría pasado el examen.* (If I had studied more, I would have passed the test.)\n\n**5️⃣ Variation in mood:**\nWhen used alone (*hubiera ido*), it expresses wistful imagination. When paired (*si hubiera ido, habría visto*), it becomes logical regret—a structure that mourns what the speaker knows cannot change."
