{
  "id": "mmspanish__lesson_B1_154_sequence_of_tenses",
  "title": "B1.154 Sequence of Tenses — Harmony Across Time",
  "mode": "mix_method",
  "steps": [
    {
      "phase": "english_anchor",
      "line": "In English, we shift verb tenses naturally to keep time consistent: 'I think she knows,' 'I thought she knew.' Spanish follows a similar logic, called **sequence of tenses**—a rule that keeps verbs in harmony between the main clause and the dependent one. When the main verb changes in time, the second verb follows it. English does this by intuition; Spanish does it by **grammaric alignment**, ensuring every clause fits the same temporal rhythm."
    },
    {
      "phase": "system_logic",
      "line": "**1️⃣ The principle:**\nThe tense of the dependent (subordinate) clause depends on the tense of the main clause. Spanish keeps time coherent by pairing moods and tenses that reflect whether the event is real, desired, or uncertain.\n\n**2️⃣ Present-time main verbs → present-time dependents:**\nIf the main verb is in the present, future, or perfect, the dependent verb uses a **present subjunctive** (if uncertain) or **present indicative** (if certain).\n- *Creo que viene.* (I think he’s coming.)\n- *Dudo que venga.* (I doubt he’s coming.)\n\n**3️⃣ Past-time main verbs → past-time dependents:**\nIf the main verb is in the preterite, imperfect, or conditional, the dependent verb shifts back to **imperfect subjunctive** or **past indicative**.\n- *Creía que venía.* (I thought he was coming.)\n- *Dudaba que viniera.* (I doubted he was coming.)\n\n**4️⃣ Quick chart:**\n| Main clause | Time | Subordinate clause | Example |\n|--------------|------|--------------------|----------|\n| Present | Real | Present indicative | *Pienso que tiene razón.* |\n| Present | Doubtful | Present subjunctive | *Dudo que tenga razón.* |\n| Past | Real | Imperfect indicative | *Pensé que tenía razón.* |\n| Past | Doubtful | Imperfect subjunctive | *Dudaba que tuviera razón.* |\n\n**5️⃣ Perfect and future references:**\nFor past events tied to the present: *Me alegra que hayas venido* (I’m glad you’ve come). For imagined futures: *Esperaba que hubieras llegado a tiempo* (I hoped you had arrived on time). Spanish uses this grammar to balance perspective—no tense floats free of its anchor."
    },
    {
      "phase": "meaning_depth",
      "origin": "The rule descends from Latin’s temporal agreement system, where subordinate verbs mirrored their main verbs in time and mood to preserve logical sequence.",
      "story": "In Spanish, time behaves like music—it demands harmony. The sequence of tenses exists to keep melody between clauses. When one verb moves into the past, the rest must follow so the rhythm stays even. The rule isn’t about rigidity—it’s about coherence.\n\nSpanish speakers hear tense as perspective. If you begin a sentence in the past (*quería*), your thoughts live there. The dependent verb (*vinieras*) keeps you inside that emotional moment. Grammar becomes storytelling—it keeps memories in their proper light.\n\nIn conversation, this pattern preserves clarity. *Pensé que venías* differs from *pensé que vienes* not only in form but in feeling. The first describes reflection; the second breaks the frame of time. Spanish protects meaning by keeping verbs faithful to the moment they belong to.\n\nWriters love this precision. They use it to shift mood, to suspend events between wish and fact. *Esperaba que llegaras temprano* sounds wistful because the verbs breathe the same air. It’s how Spanish preserves atmosphere through syntax.",
      "wrap_line": "Sequence of tenses keeps time honest—grammar that ensures every clause remembers when its story began."
    },
    {
      "phase": "context_scene",
      "npc": "teacher",
      "es": "[locked]",
      "you": "[locked]"
    },
    {
      "phase": "examples",
      "items": [
        { "en": "I think he’s coming → creo que viene.", "es": "[locked]" },
        { "en": "I thought he was coming → creía que venía.", "es": "[locked]" },
