{
  "id": "mmspanish__lesson_B1_155_si_clauses_type_1_3",
  "title": "B1.155 Si Clauses Type 1–3 — The Grammar of Possibility",
  "mode": "mix_method",
  "steps": [
    {
      "phase": "english_anchor",
      "line": "In English, we build conditional sentences with 'if': 'If it rains, I’ll stay home,' 'If I studied, I would pass,' 'If I had known, I would have come.' Spanish uses the same logic—**si clauses**—to show different levels of possibility, but the tenses must match in a precise way. English does this with 'will,' 'would,' and 'would have'; Spanish does it by pairing the **indicative, subjunctive,** and **conditional** to measure how real or unreal the condition is."
    },
    {
      "phase": "system_logic",
      "line": "**1️⃣ The three types of Si Clauses:**\nSpanish organizes conditions by **how likely or possible** the situation is.\n\n**Type 1 — Real / Likely**\nFormula: *Si + present indicative → future or present.*\n- *Si llueve, me quedo en casa.* (If it rains, I stay home.)\n- *Si estudias, aprobarás.* (If you study, you’ll pass.)\n→ The condition is realistic; the result is expected.\n\n**Type 2 — Unreal / Hypothetical Present or Future**\nFormula: *Si + imperfect subjunctive → conditional.*\n- *Si tuviera dinero, viajaría más.* (If I had money, I would travel more.)\n- *Si fueras tú, no lo haría.* (If you were me, I wouldn’t do it.)\n→ The condition is imagined, not true right now.\n\n**Type 3 — Impossible / Hypothetical Past**\nFormula: *Si + pluperfect subjunctive → conditional perfect.*\n- *Si hubiera sabido, habría venido.* (If I had known, I would have come.)\n- *Si hubieras estudiado, habrías pasado el examen.* (If you had studied, you’d have passed the test.)\n→ The condition is fully past and impossible to change.\n\n**2️⃣ Quick Comparison Table:**\n| Type | Time | Structure | Meaning |\n|------|------|------------|----------|\n| 1 | Real / present-future | *Si + present → future/present* | Possible situation |\n| 2 | Unreal / present-future | *Si + imperfect subjunctive → conditional* | Hypothetical situation |\n| 3 | Unreal / past | *Si + pluperfect subjunctive → conditional perfect* | Regret / missed event |\n\n**3️⃣ Key tip:** Spanish never mixes 'si' with future or conditional directly after it. You can’t say *si lloverá* or *si viajaría*—the first verb after *si* always looks backward in logic, not forward in time."
