  "id": "mmspanish__lesson_B1_156_si_imperfect_subjunctive_conditional",
  "title": "B1.156 Si + Imperfect Subjunctive + Conditional — The Unreal Present",
  "mode": "mix_method",
  "steps": [
    {
      "phase": "english_anchor",
      "line": "In English, we express unreal or imaginary situations with 'would'—'If I had money, I would travel,' or 'If it were sunny, we’d go out.' Spanish does the same with **si + imperfect subjunctive + conditional.** It imagines the present as if it were different. English does this by using 'would' and past verbs together; Spanish does it by pairing two time-bending moods: the **imperfect subjunctive** (the wish) and the **conditional** (the imagined result). It’s grammar for the world that isn’t—but could be."
    },
    {
      "phase": "system_logic",
      "line": "**1️⃣ Structure:**\nFormula: *Si + imperfect subjunctive → conditional.*\n- *Si tuviera dinero, viajaría más.* (If I had money, I would travel more.)\n- *Si hicieras ejercicio, te sentirías mejor.* (If you exercised, you’d feel better.)\n\n**2️⃣ How it works:**\nThe clause after *si* expresses an unreal or unlikely condition—something not true now. The second clause (the conditional) expresses what would happen if it were true.\n\n**3️⃣ Grammar Breakdown:**\n| Clause | Function | Example |\n|--------|-----------|----------|\n| Si + imperfect subjunctive | Unreal condition | *Si viviera en España* (If I lived in Spain) |\n| Conditional main clause | Imagined result | *aprendería el idioma.* (I’d learn the language.) |\n→ *Si viviera en España, aprendería el idioma.* (If I lived in Spain, I’d learn the language.)\n\n**4️⃣ Verb formation refresher:**\nImperfect subjunctive = past stem + *-ra, -ras, -ra, -ramos, -rais, -ran.*\nConditional = infinitive + *-ía, -ías, -ía, -íamos, -íais, -ían.*\nBoth keep soft endings that make the sentence sound smooth and speculative.\n\n**5️⃣ Common errors:**\n- Never use *si + conditional* → ❌ *Si tendría dinero.*\n- Never use *si + present* when imagining → ❌ *Si tengo tiempo, iría.*\nOnly *si + imperfect subjunctive* creates this 'what-if' structure.\n\n**6️⃣ Tone and variation:**\n*Si clauses* of this type carry empathy or distance. They let you dream politely (*si pudieras ayudarme...*), or imagine impossibilities (*si volara...*). The grammar doesn’t just mark unreality—it softens it into grace."
