  "id": "mmspanish__lesson_B1_157_reported_speech",
  "title": "B1.157 Reported Speech — The Grammar of Distance",
  "mode": "mix_method",
  "steps": [
    {
      "phase": "english_anchor",
      "line": "In English, we use reported speech to tell what someone said without quoting them directly: 'She said she was tired,' 'He told me he’d call.' Spanish does the same but shifts the verb tense more carefully depending on when the speech happened. English does this by using 'said' and changing helping verbs; Spanish does it by creating **time distance**—a respectful echo that shows the words now belong to memory, not the moment."
    },
    {
      "phase": "system_logic",
      "line": "**1️⃣ Direct vs. Reported (Indirect) Speech:**\n- **Direct speech:** repeats words exactly.\n  - *Ella dijo: “Estoy cansada.”* (She said, “I’m tired.”)\n- **Reported speech:** restates meaning with adjusted tenses.\n  - *Ella dijo que estaba cansada.* (She said she was tired.)\n\n**2️⃣ Backshifting tenses — how Spanish tracks time distance:**\nWhen the reporting verb is in the past (*dijo, comentó, explicó*), the verb in the subordinate clause usually shifts one step backward in time.\n| Original (direct) | After reporting | Example |\n|-------------------|-----------------|----------|\n| Present → Imperfect | *Estoy cansado* → *dijo que estaba cansado.* |\n| Preterite → Pluperfect | *Fui al cine* → *dijo que había ido al cine.* |\n| Future → Conditional | *Iré mañana* → *dijo que iría mañana.* |\n| Present perfect → Pluperfect | *He terminado* → *dijo que había terminado.* |\n\n**3️⃣ Exceptions:**\n- When the reporting verb is **present**, tense stays the same: *Dice que está cansado.* (He says he’s tired.)\n- If the fact is still true, Spanish often **keeps** the original tense: *Dijo que vive en Madrid* (She said she lives in Madrid — still true.)\n\n**4️⃣ Pronouns and time words also shift:**\n- *yo → él/ella*, *hoy → ese día*, *mañana → al día siguiente*, *aquí → allí.*\n- *Dijo: “Vendré mañana.”* → *Dijo que vendría al día siguiente.*\n\n**5️⃣ Summary:**\nReported speech in Spanish is about **perspective**. The speaker steps back from the moment, adjusting tense and time to honor what was once said without claiming it as present truth."
    },
    {
      "phase": "meaning_depth",
      "origin": "From Latin’s sequence of tenses system, Spanish preserved indirect discourse as a structured way to convey memory, truth, and perspective.",
      "story": "Spanish uses grammar to respect time. When someone says *dijo que estaba cansada*, they’re not just reporting—they’re showing care for accuracy and distance. The tense shift marks the moment when words leave the speaker and become history.\n\nThis form shapes how Spanish handles storytelling and journalism alike. Reported speech builds bridges between voices. *Me contó que había perdido el tren* isn’t just recounting—it situates you in relation to the event, one layer removed. The shift in tense becomes a gesture of humility: 'these are not my words, but I carry them.'\n\nIn culture, Spanish values fidelity to feeling as much as to fact. The backshift mirrors how memory softens with time—details fade, but essence remains. *Dijo que vendría*, even if he didn’t come, preserves intention, not disappointment. Grammar turns recollection into empathy.\n\nWriters rely on reported speech to balance closeness and distance. It allows a narrator to respect what was said while framing its meaning. In doing so, the language itself models good memory: precise, gentle, and self-aware.",
      "wrap_line": "Reported speech turns time into ethics—grammar that remembers faithfully while admitting it no longer speaks from the present."
