  "id": "mmspanish__lesson_B1_159_relative_pronouns",
  "title": "B1.159 Relative Pronouns — Que, Quien, Cuyo, Donde",
  "mode": "mix_method",
  "steps": [
    {
      "phase": "english_anchor",
      "line": "In English, we connect ideas with words like 'who,' 'that,' 'which,' and 'where': 'The man who called,' 'The book that I read,' 'The house where I grew up.' Spanish uses **relative pronouns**—**que, quien, cuyo, donde**—to do the same thing, linking clauses smoothly. English does this with helper words that follow flexible logic; Spanish does it by choosing connectors that match gender, number, and formality, turning grammar into architecture that joins one thought to another perfectly."
    },
    {
      "phase": "system_logic",
      "line": "**1️⃣ Core relative pronouns and their uses:**\n\n**QUE** → 'that, which, who' (most common, general-purpose connector)\n- *El libro que leí es interesante.* (The book that I read is interesting.)\n- *La persona que llamó era tu tía.* (The person who called was your aunt.)\nUsed for people, things, and general connections—simple and universal.\n\n**QUIEN / QUIENES** → 'who, whom' (refers only to people, often after prepositions or commas)\n- *Mi amigo, quien vive en México, me escribió.* (My friend, who lives in Mexico, wrote me.)\n- *La persona a quien saludé era amable.* (The person to whom I waved was kind.)\nNote: *quien/quienes* usually replaces *que* when the clause is non-restrictive or when following a preposition like *a, de, con, por*.\n\n**CUYO / CUYA / CUYOS / CUYAS** → 'whose' (shows possession, agrees with the noun it modifies)\n- *El hombre cuya hija conoces está aquí.* (The man whose daughter you know is here.)\n- *La casa cuyos muros son rojos es antigua.* (The house whose walls are red is old.)\n\n**DONDE** → 'where' (refers to place)\n- *El pueblo donde nací es pequeño.* (The town where I was born is small.)\n\n**2️⃣ Quick reference table:**\n| Pronoun | Meaning | Refers to | Notes |\n|----------|----------|------------|--------|\n| que | that / which / who | people or things | Most versatile, no preposition needed |\n| quien/es | who / whom | people | After prepositions or commas |\n| cuyo/a/os/as | whose | possession | Matches following noun’s gender and number |\n| donde | where | places | Can mean 'in which' or 'at which' |\n\n**3️⃣ Common errors:**\n- Never confuse *cuyo* with *de quien*—they aren’t interchangeable. *El hombre cuyo coche* (The man whose car) ≠ *El hombre de quien el coche.*\n- *Que* is neutral; *quien* adds elegance and formality.\nSpanish uses these to balance flow, clarity, and tone."
    },
