{
  "id": "mmspanish__lesson_B1_162_por_vs_para_master",
  "title": "B1.162 Por vs. Para (Master Level) — Purpose, Exchange, Cause",
  "mode": "mix_method",
  "steps": [
    {
      "phase": "english_anchor",
      "line": "In English, we use 'for' to mean many different things: 'for you,' 'for an hour,' 'for the test,' 'for my mother.' Spanish divides that idea between **por** and **para**, each with its own focus. **Por** explains reason, cause, or movement through something; **para** explains purpose, destination, or final goal. English does this with one flexible preposition; Spanish does it by splitting motive from intention—why something happens versus what it’s for."
    },
    {
      "phase": "system_logic",
      "line": "**1️⃣ Core Distinction:**\nThink of *por* as **because of** and *para* as **in order to.**\n\n| Function | POR | PARA |\n|-----------|------|------|\n| Meaning | cause / reason / exchange / movement | purpose / goal / recipient / destination |\n| Question answered | Why? How? Through what? | For what? For whom? Toward what? |\n\n**2️⃣ Common Uses of POR:**\n- **Cause or reason:** *Lo hice por ti.* (I did it because of you.)\n- **Exchange:** *Te doy cinco euros por el libro.* (I’ll give you five euros for the book.)\n- **Duration of time:** *Viví allí por tres años.* (I lived there for three years.)\n- **Movement through space:** *Caminamos por el parque.* (We walked through the park.)\n- **Means or method:** *Hablamos por teléfono.* (We talked by phone.)\n- **Passive voice agent:** *Fue escrito por Cervantes.* (It was written by Cervantes.)\n\n**3️⃣ Common Uses of PARA:**\n- **Goal or purpose:** *Estudio para aprender.* (I study in order to learn.)\n- **Destination or direction:** *Salgo para Madrid mañana.* (I’m leaving for Madrid tomorrow.)\n- **Recipient:** *Este regalo es para ti.* (This gift is for you.)\n- **Deadline or specific time:** *La tarea es para mañana.* (The homework is for tomorrow.)\n- **Comparison / opinion:** *Para ser tan joven, es sabio.* (For being so young, he’s wise.)\n- **Employment:** *Trabajo para una empresa grande.* (I work for a big company.)\n\n**4️⃣ Visual Trick:**\nImagine *por* as a **journey through cause and medium**, and *para* as an **arrow pointing to purpose or destination.** *Por* moves within; *para* moves toward.\n\n**5️⃣ Common mistakes:**\n- ❌ *Gracias para venir.* ✅ *Gracias por venir.* (Thanks for coming — cause, not goal.)\n- ❌ *Voy por España.* ✅ *Voy para España.* (I’m going to Spain — destination, not route.)\n- *Por* answers 'why' and 'how'; *para* answers 'what for' and 'where to.'"
    },
    {
      "phase": "meaning_depth",
      "origin": "Both prepositions descend from Latin—*pro* (for, in favor of) and *per* (through)—retaining their distinct senses of direction versus motive.",
      "story": "The battle of *por* and *para* is really a dialogue about intention. Spanish divides human action into two sides: movement and meaning. *Por* speaks of the path—the reason, the sacrifice, the journey through something. *Para* speaks of the goal—the point on the horizon you move toward.\n\nEveryday speech reveals this philosophy. *Gracias por venir* thanks someone for effort, for motion through time. *Esto es para ti* dedicates the result, the outcome. One looks backward to origin; the other looks forward to purpose. Together, they capture the full arc of experience.\n\nIn Latin America, *por amor* and *para amar* express different truths. The first explains motive—'because of love.' The second expresses intention—'in order to love.' It’s the same word in English, but Spanish insists the soul knows two directions.\n\nWriters use *por* and *para* to weigh choice and destiny. *Viajó por el mundo para encontrarse a sí mismo.* (He traveled through the world to find himself.) The sentence carries both—the wandering and the reason for it. Grammar becomes philosophy: a record of where you’ve been and why you keep going.",
      "wrap_line": "*Por* traces the road we walk; *para* draws the destination ahead—grammar that balances reason with purpose, cause with hope."
    },
