  "id": "mmspanish__lesson_B1_163_prepositions_place_advanced",
  "title": "B1.163 Prepositions of Place (Advanced) — Desde, Hacia, Contra",
  "mode": "mix_method",
  "steps": [
    {
      "phase": "english_anchor",
      "line": "In English, we use words like 'from,' 'toward,' and 'against' to show direction and relation in space: 'from here,' 'toward the door,' 'leaning against the wall.' Spanish mirrors this through **desde, hacia,** and **contra**, each adding nuance to how motion or position is perceived. English does this by focusing on position alone; Spanish does it by revealing the relationship—distance, intent, or opposition—within the movement itself."
    },
    {
      "phase": "system_logic",
      "line": "**1️⃣ DESDE → Starting point (from, since).**\nShows **origin in space or time**—the place or moment something begins.\n- *Viene desde México.* (He’s coming from Mexico.)\n- *Trabajo aquí desde 2015.* (I’ve worked here since 2015.)\n*Desde* often pairs with *hasta* (until) to mark a range: *desde el amanecer hasta la noche.*\n\n**2️⃣ HACIA → Direction or tendency (toward, about).**\nShows **approximate movement or orientation**, physical or abstract.\n- *Camina hacia el norte.* (She walks toward the north.)\n- *Su actitud hacia mí cambió.* (His attitude toward me changed.)\n- *La temperatura estará hacia los 30 grados.* (The temperature will be around 30 degrees.)\nUnlike *a*, which marks arrival, *hacia* suggests **approach without arrival**—movement still in progress.\n\n**3️⃣ CONTRA → Contact or opposition (against).**\nShows **resistance, impact, or disagreement.**\n- *Apoya la espalda contra la pared.* (Rest your back against the wall.)\n- *Luchan contra la injusticia.* (They fight against injustice.)\n- *El viento sopla contra la ventana.* (The wind blows against the window.)\nWhen figurative, *contra* expresses moral or ideological opposition—where struggle replaces contact.\n\n**4️⃣ Quick comparison chart:**\n| Preposition | Core Meaning | Typical Use |\n|--------------|---------------|--------------|\n| desde | from, since | origin or starting point |\n| hacia | toward, around | direction or tendency |\n| contra | against | opposition or contact |\n\n**5️⃣ Subtle contrasts:**\n- *Desde* measures where something **begins**; *hacia* measures where it’s **headed.***\n- *Contra* marks where resistance **meets** it. Together, they map movement through, toward, and against space and thought."
    },
    {
      "phase": "meaning_depth",
      "origin": "From Latin prepositions *de ex*, *ad versum*, and *contra*, each evolved to define relation—whether departure, direction, or defiance.",
      "story": "Spanish prepositions carry philosophy in miniature. *Desde* speaks of beginnings—it frames distance as story. *Hacia* points forward, showing effort or intention without demanding an end. *Contra* names struggle, the place where force meets will.\n\nIn Spanish expression, these prepositions reach beyond geography. *Desde el alma* ('from the soul') marks origin not in space but emotion. *Hacia el futuro* (‘toward the future’) expresses optimism—a step more poetic than 'to the future.' *Contra el miedo* ('against fear') turns grammar into courage.\n\nWriters and speakers use these words to build emotional direction. A relationship might move *hacia la confianza*—toward trust—or break *contra los prejuicios*—against prejudice. Each preposition charts inner terrain. Spanish doesn’t just map motion; it traces motive. The same prepositions that locate bodies can locate beliefs.\n\nOver centuries, *desde, hacia, contra* became tools for poetry and protest alike. They teach that movement, in language as in life, is never just about where—it’s about why and how we go.",
      "wrap_line": "In Spanish, prepositions mark not only position but perspective—grammar that tracks the soul’s direction as much as the body’s."
