  "id": "mmspanish__lesson_B1_164_prepositions_time",
  "title": "B1.164 Prepositions of Time — Desde, Hasta, Durante, En",
  "mode": "mix_method",
  "steps": [
    {
      "phase": "english_anchor",
      "line": "In English, we use time prepositions like 'from,' 'until,' 'during,' and 'in' to mark when something happens: 'from Monday to Friday,' 'during the day,' 'in the morning.' Spanish mirrors these ideas through **desde, hasta, durante,** and **en.** Each describes how time stretches, limits, or contains an event. English does this with separate words for each situation; Spanish does it by treating time like a journey—each preposition tracing its beginning, path, and end."
    },
    {
      "phase": "system_logic",
      "line": "**1️⃣ DESDE → From / Since (starting point in time).**\nIndicates **when something begins.** Works with moments or durations.\n- *Trabajo aquí desde 2018.* (I’ve worked here since 2018.)\n- *Desde que llegué, no he parado.* (Since I arrived, I haven’t stopped.)\nOften pairs with *hasta* to define a full range: *desde las ocho hasta las diez.*\n\n**2️⃣ HASTA → Until / Up to (end point in time).**\nMarks the **limit or closure** of an action.\n- *Estudié hasta la medianoche.* (I studied until midnight.)\n- *La tienda está abierta hasta las nueve.* (The store is open until nine.)\nCan also indicate expectations: *Hasta mañana* (See you until tomorrow → See you tomorrow.)\n\n**3️⃣ DURANTE → During / For (duration within a timeframe).**\nDescribes **how long** something lasts.\n- *Durmió durante ocho horas.* (He slept for eight hours.)\n- *Durante el verano, viajamos mucho.* (During the summer, we traveled a lot.)\nUsed for continuous or defined periods without specifying start or end.\n\n**4️⃣ EN → In / On / At (position within time).**\nShows **a point or general container of time.**\n- *En enero hace frío.* (It’s cold in January.)\n- *Nos vemos en cinco minutos.* (See you in five minutes.)\n- *En la mañana tomo café.* (In the morning I drink coffee.)\n\n**5️⃣ Comparison Table:**\n| Preposition | Meaning | Focus |\n|--------------|----------|--------|\n| desde | from / since | beginning |\n| hasta | until | ending |\n| durante | during / for | duration |\n| en | in / on / at | placement |\n\n**6️⃣ Tip:**\n*Desde* and *hasta* map the **edges** of time; *durante* describes what happens **within** it; *en* anchors the **moment itself.** Spanish measures time not by numbers, but by relationship."
