{
  "id": "mmspanish__lesson_B1_165_subjunctive_with_emotion",
  "title": "B1.165 Subjunctive with Emotion — Grammar of Reaction",
  "mode": "mix_method",
  "steps": [
    {
      "phase": "english_anchor",
      "line": "In English, emotion often shows up as tone: 'I’m happy you’re here,' 'I’m sad he left,' 'I’m surprised she called.' Spanish expresses the same feelings with grammar—specifically, the **subjunctive mood.** When one person’s emotion reacts to another’s action, the verb in the second clause changes to the subjunctive. English shows emotion through words or voice; Spanish does it by shifting the verb, making grammar itself feel what the speaker feels."
    },
    {
      "phase": "system_logic",
      "line": "**1️⃣ Structure:**\nFormula: *[Emotion verb + que + subjunctive clause].*\n- *Me alegra que estés aquí.* (I’m glad you’re here.)\n- *Siento que no puedas venir.* (I’m sorry you can’t come.)\n- *Temo que se haya perdido.* (I’m afraid he’s gotten lost.)\n\n**2️⃣ Core rule:**\nWhen the sentence has **two different subjects** and the first expresses **emotion, hope, fear, or reaction**, the verb in the second clause must be **subjunctive.**\n- *Estoy contento de que vengas.* (I’m happy you’re coming.)\n- *Nos molesta que griten tanto.* (It bothers us that they yell so much.)\nIf both parts share the same subject, use the **infinitive** instead:\n- *Me alegra estar aquí.* (I’m glad to be here.)\n\n**3️⃣ Common emotion triggers:**\n| Emotion | Example Verb | Example Sentence |\n|----------|----------------|------------------|\n| Joy | alegrarse de que | *Me alegro de que ganes.* (I’m glad you win.) |\n| Sadness | sentir que | *Siento que estés triste.* (I’m sorry you’re sad.) |\n| Fear | temer que | *Temo que no llegues a tiempo.* (I’m afraid you won’t arrive on time.) |\n| Surprise | sorprenderse de que | *Me sorprende que digas eso.* (I’m surprised you say that.) |\n| Anger | molestar que | *Le molesta que lo interrumpan.* (It bothers him when they interrupt.) |\n\n**4️⃣ Tense consistency:**\nIf the main clause is in the present → use **present subjunctive.**\nIf it’s in the past → use **imperfect subjunctive.**\n- *Me alegró que vinieras.* (I was glad you came.)\nSpanish time-shifts emotion the same way it time-shifts fact."
    },
    {
      "phase": "meaning_depth",
      "origin": "From Latin’s subjunctive system of emotional dependence, Spanish preserved the link between feeling and uncertainty, where grammar bends under the weight of emotion.",
