  "id": "mmspanish__lesson_B1_168_subjunctive_with_adverbial_clauses",
  "title": "B1.168 Subjunctive with Adverbial Clauses — Grammar of Contingency",
  "mode": "mix_method",
  "steps": [
    {
      "phase": "english_anchor",
      "line": "In English, we express conditions or timing with words like 'before,' 'unless,' or 'in case': 'Call me before you leave,' 'I’ll go unless it rains.' Spanish does the same, but when the action in the second clause is **uncertain or depends on something else**, it switches to the **subjunctive mood.** English marks possibility with context and tone; Spanish marks it with grammar, showing whether an action is definite, pending, or conditional on another event."
    },
    {
      "phase": "system_logic",
      "line": "**1️⃣ Core idea:**\nUse the **subjunctive** after conjunctions that express **condition, purpose, or anticipation** when the action is not yet completed or depends on another event.\n\n**Formula:** *Main clause + conjunction + verb (subjunctive if uncertain / indicative if habitual or completed).* \n\n**2️⃣ Common conjunctions that trigger the subjunctive:**\n| Type | Spanish | Meaning |\n|------|----------|----------|\n| Purpose | *para que* | so that |\n| Condition | *a menos que, con tal que, en caso de que* | unless, provided that, in case |\n| Time / Anticipation | *antes de que, hasta que, cuando, en cuanto* | before, until, when, as soon as |\n\n**3️⃣ Examples:**\n- *Te llamaré antes de que salgas.* (I’ll call you before you leave.) → future, not yet done → **subjunctive.**\n- *Siempre me llama antes de que salgo.* ❌ → *Siempre me llama antes de salir.* ✅ (Habitual → infinitive.)\n- *No salgas sin que te diga adiós.* (Don’t leave without me saying goodbye.)\n- *En caso de que llueva, cancelaremos el partido.* (In case it rains, we’ll cancel the game.)\n\n**4️⃣ Contrast with indicative:**\nIf the clause describes something **completed or habitual**, use the **indicative.**\n- *Siempre me llama cuando llega.* (He always calls when he arrives.) → Habitual → indicative.\n- *Me llamará cuando llegue.* (He will call when he arrives.) → Future / uncertain → subjunctive.\n\n**5️⃣ Tip:**\nThe subjunctive lives where **certainty hasn’t happened yet.** If time, condition, or purpose still hang in the air, Spanish shifts to the subjunctive to capture that suspense."
