  "mode": "mix_method",
  "steps": [
    {
      "phase": "english_anchor",
      "line": "In English, time connectors like 'when,' 'until,' or 'before' tell us when something happens: 'I’ll call you when I arrive,' 'Wait until he comes,' 'Finish before it rains.' Spanish uses these same connectors—**cuando, hasta que, antes de que**—but changes the verb to the **subjunctive** when the action hasn’t yet occurred or depends on something uncertain. English expresses this future feeling with context; Spanish marks it with mood, turning time into grammar."
    },
    {
      "phase": "system_logic",
      "line": "**1️⃣ The Core Rule:**\nAfter time expressions that refer to a **future or uncompleted event**, Spanish requires the **subjunctive.** If the action is **habitual or already completed**, it uses the **indicative.**\n\n| Meaning | Connector | Verb Form | Example |\n|----------|------------|------------|----------|\n| Future / uncertain | cuando, hasta que, antes de que | subjunctive | *Te llamaré cuando llegue.* (I’ll call you when I arrive.) |\n| Habitual / completed | cuando, hasta que, antes de que | indicative | *Siempre me llama cuando llega.* (He always calls when he arrives.) |\n\n**2️⃣ Common Temporal Conjunctions:**\n| Spanish | English | Subjunctive trigger? |\n|----------|----------|---------------------|\n| cuando | when | yes, if future/unreal |\n| hasta que | until | yes, if pending |\n| antes de que | before | always subjunctive |\n| después de que | after | yes, if pending |\n| en cuanto / tan pronto como | as soon as | yes, if pending |\n\n**3️⃣ Examples in context:**\n- *No salgas hasta que termine la reunión.* (Don’t leave until the meeting ends.) → Future, **subjunctive.**\n- *Salimos cuando termina la reunión.* (We leave when the meeting ends.) → Habitual, **indicative.**\n- *Te escribiré tan pronto como pueda.* (I’ll write as soon as I can.) → Future, **subjunctive.**\n- *Lo hizo después de que llegó.* (He did it after he arrived.) → Completed, **indicative.**\n\n**4️⃣ Special note — antes de que:**\nAlways uses the subjunctive because it describes an action that hasn’t yet occurred relative to another.\n- *Estudia antes de que salgas.* (Study before you leave.)\n\n**5️⃣ Tip:**\nIf the event lies in the **future or uncertainty**, the subjunctive steps in. Spanish hears time as alive—unfixed until it happens."
