{
  "id": "mmspanish__lesson_B1_170_indicative_vs_subjunctive_summary",
  "title": "B1.170 Indicative vs. Subjunctive Summary — Mood by Meaning",
  "mode": "mix_method",
  "steps": [
    {
      "phase": "english_anchor",
      "line": "In English, we use tone or extra words to show certainty or doubt: 'I think he’s coming' versus 'I hope he comes.' Spanish captures that difference with **mood**, not just vocabulary. The **indicative** expresses what’s real, known, or observable; the **subjunctive** expresses what’s uncertain, desired, or imagined. English handles reality versus possibility through meaning and phrasing; Spanish does it directly through the verb, making emotion and logic visible in grammar."
    },
    {
      "phase": "system_logic",
      "line": "**1️⃣ The Two Worlds of Mood:**\n| Mood | Purpose | Example |\n|-------|----------|----------|\n| Indicative | Facts, reality, and certainty | *Sé que viene.* (I know he’s coming.) |\n| Subjunctive | Doubt, emotion, desire, unreality | *Dudo que venga.* (I doubt he’s coming.) |\n\n**2️⃣ How They Work:**\n- The **indicative** reports events as the speaker believes them to be true.\n- The **subjunctive** appears when the speaker’s mind introduces subjectivity—feelings, doubt, influence, or imagination.\n\n**3️⃣ Common Triggers:**\n| Category | Example Phrases | Verb Mood |\n|-----------|----------------|------------|\n| Belief / certainty | *creer que, estar seguro de que, es cierto que* | Indicative |\n| Emotion / desire | *esperar que, sentir que, temer que* | Subjunctive |\n| Doubt / denial | *no creer que, dudar que, no es verdad que* | Subjunctive |\n| Impersonal expressions | *es obvio que, es verdad que* (indicative) / *es posible que, es necesario que* (subjunctive) |\n| Nonexistent or indefinite subjects | *busco un libro que explique esto* | Subjunctive |\n\n**4️⃣ Reality Test:**\nAsk: Does the speaker treat the situation as **real or certain**? If yes → indicative. If not → subjunctive.\n- *Pienso que tienes razón.* (I think you’re right.) → belief = **indicative.**\n- *No pienso que tengas razón.* (I don’t think you’re right.) → doubt = **subjunctive.**\n\n**5️⃣ Tense Connection:**\nThe choice of mood stays consistent even when tenses shift. Whether in the present, past, or conditional, mood depends on meaning, not time:\n- *Espero que vengas.* (I hope you come.)\n- *Esperaba que vinieras.* (I hoped you would come.)\n\nSpanish doesn’t just tell time—it tells perspective."
    },
    {
      "phase": "meaning_depth",
      "origin": "From Latin’s split between the factual 'indicativus' and the hypothetical 'subiunctivus,' Spanish inherited both logic and emotion within its verbs.",
      "story": "The dance between indicative and subjunctive defines Spanish thought. The indicative belongs to what’s visible—the world of proof. The subjunctive belongs to what’s felt—the world of possibility. The two moods don’t compete; they complete each other.\n\nIn conversation, the indicative grounds the speaker: *sé que vienes* is confidence made grammatical. The subjunctive, on the other hand, opens the heart: *ojalá que vengas* lives in hope. Spanish moves between these worlds fluidly, because life does too. It knows that truth and feeling coexist.\n\nThis mood distinction shapes culture as much as language. Spanish doesn’t separate emotion from grammar—it dignifies it. When someone says *no creo que sea posible,* they’re not being dramatic—they’re honoring the uncertainty that defines being human.\n\nWriters, philosophers, and lovers lean on the subjunctive to describe the almosts and maybes of life. The indicative says 'it is.' The subjunctive whispers 'it could be.'",
      "wrap_line": "The indicative speaks of what is; the subjunctive dreams of what might be—grammar that holds certainty in one hand and hope in the other."
    },
